1
00:00:27,569 --> 00:00:32,574
[girl singing]

2
00:00:42,626 --> 00:00:45,629
<i>♪ Yo ho
Yo ho</i>

3
00:00:45,712 --> 00:00:48,757
<i>♪ A pirate's life for me</i>

4
00:00:48,799 --> 00:00:53,595
<i>♪ We extort, we pilfer
We filch, we sack</i>

5
00:00:53,637 --> 00:00:56,139
<i>- ♪ Drink…</i> [gasps]
- Quiet, missy!

6
00:00:56,223 --> 00:00:58,600
Cursed pirates sail these waters.

7
00:00:58,642 --> 00:01:00,936
You don't want to bring
them down on us, do ya?

8
00:01:00,978 --> 00:01:02,813
Mr Gibbs, that will do.

9
00:01:03,605 --> 00:01:05,482
She was singing about pirates!

10
00:01:05,524 --> 00:01:07,651
Bad luck to be singing about pirates

11
00:01:07,734 --> 00:01:10,904
with us mired in this unnatural fog,
mark my words.

12
00:01:10,988 --> 00:01:12,322
Consider them marked.

13
00:01:14,074 --> 00:01:16,493
- On your way.
- Aye, lieutenant.

14
00:01:16,577 --> 00:01:18,662
It's bad luck to have
a woman on board too.

15
00:01:18,704 --> 00:01:20,956
Even a miniature one.

16
00:01:22,082 --> 00:01:24,543
I think it'd be rather exciting
to meet a pirate.

17
00:01:26,253 --> 00:01:28,338
Think again, Miss Swann.

18
00:01:28,422 --> 00:01:31,258
Vile and dissolute creatures,
the lot of 'em.

19
00:01:31,341 --> 00:01:34,469
I intend to see to it that any man
who sails under a pirate flag

20
00:01:34,511 --> 00:01:37,139
or wears a pirate brand
gets what he deserves.

21
00:01:38,348 --> 00:01:40,517
A short drop and a sudden stop.

22
00:01:44,563 --> 00:01:47,190
Lieutenant Norrington,
I appreciate your fervour,

23
00:01:47,232 --> 00:01:51,862
but I'm concerned about the effect
this subject will have upon my daughter.

24
00:01:51,945 --> 00:01:53,739
My apologies, Governor Swann.

25
00:01:53,822 --> 00:01:56,033
Actually, I find it all fascinating.

26
00:01:56,116 --> 00:01:57,868
Yes. That's what concerns me.

27
00:02:26,146 --> 00:02:28,565
Look! A boy!
There's a boy in the water!

28
00:02:31,026 --> 00:02:32,986
[Norrington] Man overboard!

29
00:02:34,237 --> 00:02:35,947
Man the ropes!
Fetch a hook!

30
00:02:36,782 --> 00:02:38,116
Haul him aboard!

31
00:02:46,667 --> 00:02:48,585
He's still breathing.

32
00:02:48,669 --> 00:02:50,921
Mary, Mother of God!

33
00:02:57,386 --> 00:02:58,929
[Swann] What happened here?

34
00:03:00,430 --> 00:03:04,142
Most likely the powder magazine.
Merchant vessels run heavily armed.

35
00:03:06,186 --> 00:03:07,771
[Gibbs] Lot of good it did them.

36
00:03:07,854 --> 00:03:10,440
Everyone's thinking it,
I'm just saying it.

37
00:03:11,316 --> 00:03:12,526
Pirates!

38
00:03:12,609 --> 00:03:15,445
There's no proof of that!

39
00:03:15,487 --> 00:03:17,030
It was probably an accident.

40
00:03:18,615 --> 00:03:20,409
[Norrington] Rouse the captain.

41
00:03:20,450 --> 00:03:22,369
- Aye, sir.
- Heave to and take in sail.

42
00:03:22,452 --> 00:03:24,121
- Launch the boats.
- Heave to!

43
00:03:26,289 --> 00:03:28,625
Elizabeth, I want you
to accompany the boy.

44
00:03:29,793 --> 00:03:31,128
He'll be in your charge.

45
00:03:31,169 --> 00:03:32,838
Take care of him.

46
00:03:50,897 --> 00:03:53,817
- [gasps]
- It's OK.

47
00:03:53,900 --> 00:03:56,653
- [boy panting]
- My name's Elizabeth Swann.

48
00:03:57,988 --> 00:03:59,406
Will Turner.

49
00:04:00,407 --> 00:04:02,325
I'm watching over you, Will.

50
00:04:15,130 --> 00:04:17,090
You're a pirate!

51
00:04:17,174 --> 00:04:19,092
Has he said anything?

52
00:04:19,176 --> 00:04:20,761
His name's William Turner.

53
00:04:20,844 --> 00:04:22,345
That's all I found out.

54
00:04:23,346 --> 00:04:25,557
Take him below.

55
00:05:33,750 --> 00:05:34,918
[knock on door]

56
00:05:34,960 --> 00:05:36,753
[Swann] Elizabeth!

57
00:05:38,588 --> 00:05:39,756
Are you all right?

58
00:05:41,174 --> 00:05:42,300
Are you decent?

59
00:05:42,926 --> 00:05:43,927
Yes.

60
00:05:43,969 --> 00:05:44,970
Yes?

61
00:05:46,471 --> 00:05:47,931
Still in bed at this hour?

62
00:05:49,975 --> 00:05:52,269
It's a beautiful day.

63
00:05:53,770 --> 00:05:55,355
I have a gift for you.

64
00:05:58,316 --> 00:06:01,278
- Oh, it's beautiful!
- Isn't it?

65
00:06:02,946 --> 00:06:05,365
May I inquire as to the occasion?

66
00:06:05,448 --> 00:06:08,869
Does a father need an occasion
to dote upon his daughter?

67
00:06:08,952 --> 00:06:10,996
[laughs] Go on.

68
00:06:14,457 --> 00:06:15,959
Actually, I...

69
00:06:17,627 --> 00:06:20,255
I had hoped you might wear it
for the ceremony today.

70
00:06:20,297 --> 00:06:21,590
[Elizabeth] Ceremony?

71
00:06:21,631 --> 00:06:24,050
Captain Norrington's promotion ceremony.

72
00:06:24,134 --> 00:06:25,302
I knew it!

73
00:06:25,385 --> 00:06:28,680
Commodore Norrington,
as he's about to become.

74
00:06:28,763 --> 00:06:30,682
A fine gentleman, don't you think?

75
00:06:31,474 --> 00:06:32,976
He fancies you, you know.

76
00:06:33,018 --> 00:06:35,061
- [gasping]
- Elizabeth?

77
00:06:35,145 --> 00:06:36,813
How's it coming?

78
00:06:36,897 --> 00:06:39,482
It's difficult to say.

79
00:06:39,566 --> 00:06:41,818
I'm told it's
the latest fashion in London.

80
00:06:41,860 --> 00:06:43,236
Well, women in London

81
00:06:43,320 --> 00:06:44,988
must've learned not to breathe!

82
00:06:47,157 --> 00:06:48,825
My Lord, you have a visitor.

83
00:07:07,135 --> 00:07:08,345
Ah, Mr Turner.

84
00:07:08,386 --> 00:07:09,846
Good to see you again.

85
00:07:09,930 --> 00:07:11,765
Good day, sir.

86
00:07:12,682 --> 00:07:13,850
I have your order.

87
00:07:19,356 --> 00:07:20,523
Well...

88
00:07:20,607 --> 00:07:22,359
The blade is folded steel.

89
00:07:22,442 --> 00:07:25,445
That's gold filigree
laid into the handle.

90
00:07:26,154 --> 00:07:27,405
If I may?

91
00:07:29,574 --> 00:07:31,034
Perfectly balanced.

92
00:07:31,826 --> 00:07:34,120
The tang is nearly
the full width of the blade.

93
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:39,209
Impressive. Very impressive.

94
00:07:39,250 --> 00:07:40,585
Very nice.

95
00:07:41,252 --> 00:07:44,255
Commodore Norrington's going
to be very pleased with this.

96
00:07:45,382 --> 00:07:47,884
Do pass my compliments
onto your master.

97
00:07:50,053 --> 00:07:51,054
I shall.

98
00:07:52,514 --> 00:07:55,850
A craftsman is always pleased
to hear his work is appreciated.

99
00:07:57,352 --> 00:08:00,855
Elizabeth!
You look absolutely stunning.

100
00:08:00,897 --> 00:08:02,732
Will.

101
00:08:03,066 --> 00:08:05,902
It's so good to see you.

102
00:08:05,986 --> 00:08:07,654
I had a dream about you last night.

103
00:08:07,737 --> 00:08:08,738
About me?

104
00:08:08,822 --> 00:08:10,490
Is it entirely proper for you...?

105
00:08:10,573 --> 00:08:12,367
About the day we met.
Do you remember?

106
00:08:12,409 --> 00:08:15,245
How could I forget, Miss Swarm?

107
00:08:15,286 --> 00:08:17,789
How many times must I ask you
to call me Elizabeth?

108
00:08:17,872 --> 00:08:20,166
At least once more, Miss Swarm.

109
00:08:20,250 --> 00:08:22,085
As always.

110
00:08:22,127 --> 00:08:23,420
Now, you see?

111
00:08:23,461 --> 00:08:25,755
At least the boy
has a sense of propriety.

112
00:08:25,839 --> 00:08:27,090
We really must be going.

113
00:08:27,132 --> 00:08:28,133
Come on.

114
00:08:29,467 --> 00:08:30,760
Good day, Mr Turner.

115
00:08:32,345 --> 00:08:33,346
Come along!

116
00:08:36,725 --> 00:08:37,934
Good day...

117
00:08:40,770 --> 00:08:42,272
…Elizabeth.

118
00:09:43,458 --> 00:09:47,253
- [goat bleating]
- [men chattering]

119
00:10:11,986 --> 00:10:12,987
[stammering]

120
00:10:13,029 --> 00:10:14,656
Hold up there, you!

121
00:10:16,324 --> 00:10:19,661
It's a shilling to tie up
your boat to the dock.

122
00:10:21,663 --> 00:10:23,373
And I shall need to know your name.

123
00:10:26,042 --> 00:10:28,336
What do you say to three shillings,

124
00:10:28,378 --> 00:10:29,629
and we forget the name?

125
00:10:33,091 --> 00:10:35,301
Welcome to Port Royal, Mr Smith.

126
00:10:39,806 --> 00:10:41,057
[jingling]

127
00:10:41,099 --> 00:10:45,520
[drumming]

128
00:10:45,562 --> 00:10:50,567
[flutes playing]

129
00:11:11,754 --> 00:11:13,590
[man] Two paces... march!

130
00:11:16,134 --> 00:11:18,136
Right about... face!

131
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:23,433
Present... arms!

132
00:11:47,707 --> 00:11:50,460
This dock is off-limits to civilians.

133
00:11:50,543 --> 00:11:52,295
I'm terribly sorry, I didn't know.

134
00:11:52,337 --> 00:11:55,048
If I see one,
I shall inform you immediately.

135
00:11:58,635 --> 00:12:02,263
Apparently, there's some high-toned
and fancy to-do up at the fort, eh?

136
00:12:02,305 --> 00:12:05,475
How could it be two upstanding
gentlemen, such as yourselves,

137
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:07,518
did not merit an invitation?

138
00:12:07,602 --> 00:12:10,772
Someone has to make sure this dock
stays off-limits to civilians.

139
00:12:10,813 --> 00:12:13,191
It's a fine goal, to be sure.

140
00:12:13,274 --> 00:12:15,235
But it seems to me, a...

141
00:12:15,318 --> 00:12:17,070
A ship like that...

142
00:12:17,153 --> 00:12:20,156
...makes this one here
a bit superfluous, really.

143
00:12:20,198 --> 00:12:23,326
Oh, the <i>Dauntless</i> is the power
in these waters, true enough,

144
00:12:23,368 --> 00:12:27,330
but there's no ship that can match
the <i>Interceptor</i> for speed.

145
00:12:27,372 --> 00:12:28,456
I've heard of one.

146
00:12:28,498 --> 00:12:31,167
It's supposed to be very fast,
nigh uncatchable.

147
00:12:31,251 --> 00:12:33,002
The <i>Black Pearl.</i>

148
00:12:33,670 --> 00:12:35,505
[chuckling]

149
00:12:35,546 --> 00:12:37,048
There's no real ship

150
00:12:37,131 --> 00:12:38,800
that can match the <i>Interceptor.</i>

151
00:12:40,468 --> 00:12:42,512
The <i>Black Pearl</i> is a real ship.

152
00:12:42,553 --> 00:12:44,180
No. No, it's not.

153
00:12:44,222 --> 00:12:45,556
Yes, it is. I've seen it!

154
00:12:46,307 --> 00:12:47,392
You've seen it?

155
00:12:47,475 --> 00:12:50,353
- Yes.
- [soldier 1] You haven't seen it!

156
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:53,147
- [soldier 2] Yes, I have!
- [soldier 1] You've seen a ship

157
00:12:53,189 --> 00:12:55,191
with black sails,

158
00:12:55,275 --> 00:12:56,943
that's crewed by the damned,

159
00:12:57,026 --> 00:12:59,529
and captained by a man so evil

160
00:12:59,570 --> 00:13:02,198
that hell itself spat him back out?

161
00:13:02,991 --> 00:13:03,992
No.

162
00:13:04,033 --> 00:13:05,243
No.

163
00:13:05,994 --> 00:13:08,413
But I have seen a ship
with black sails.

164
00:13:08,496 --> 00:13:11,374
Oh... And no ship that's
not crewed by the damned,

165
00:13:11,457 --> 00:13:14,210
and captained by a man so evil
that hell spat him back out

166
00:13:14,252 --> 00:13:15,878
could possibly have black sails,

167
00:13:15,962 --> 00:13:18,214
therefore couldn't possibly
be any other ship

168
00:13:18,256 --> 00:13:21,718
than the <i>Black Pearl,</i>
is that what you're saying?

169
00:13:21,759 --> 00:13:22,885
No.

170
00:13:22,927 --> 00:13:24,220
Like I said,

171
00:13:24,304 --> 00:13:27,515
there's no real ship
that can match the <i>Interceptor…</i>

172
00:13:29,976 --> 00:13:30,977
Hey!

173
00:13:32,437 --> 00:13:33,438
You!

174
00:13:33,938 --> 00:13:35,606
- [gun cocks]
- Get away from there!

175
00:13:35,690 --> 00:13:38,067
You don't have permission
to be aboard there!

176
00:13:38,109 --> 00:13:39,819
Sorry. It's such a pretty boat.

177
00:13:39,902 --> 00:13:40,903
Ship!

178
00:13:41,654 --> 00:13:42,655
What's your name?

179
00:13:42,739 --> 00:13:43,740
Smith!

180
00:13:43,781 --> 00:13:45,533
Or Smithy, if you like.

181
00:13:45,575 --> 00:13:48,870
What's your purpose in Port Royal,
Mr Smith?

182
00:13:48,911 --> 00:13:49,912
Yeah, and no lies!

183
00:13:49,996 --> 00:13:51,456
All right then.

184
00:13:51,539 --> 00:13:52,540
I confess.

185
00:13:52,957 --> 00:13:56,252
It is my intention to commandeer
one of these ships, pick up a crew

186
00:13:56,336 --> 00:13:59,756
in Tortuga to rape, pillage, and pilfer
my weasely black guts out.

187
00:13:59,797 --> 00:14:01,716
I said, no lies!

188
00:14:01,758 --> 00:14:03,676
I think he's telling the truth.

189
00:14:03,760 --> 00:14:05,303
If he were telling the truth,

190
00:14:05,386 --> 00:14:06,637
he wouldn't have told us.

191
00:14:07,597 --> 00:14:11,142
Unless he knew you wouldn't believe
the truth, even if he told it to you.

192
00:14:21,861 --> 00:14:23,237
May I have a moment?

193
00:14:32,205 --> 00:14:33,956
You look lovely, Elizabeth.

194
00:14:33,998 --> 00:14:35,792
[laughs] Yes.

195
00:14:36,876 --> 00:14:39,545
I apologise if I seem forward,

196
00:14:39,629 --> 00:14:41,714
but I must speak my mind.

197
00:14:44,592 --> 00:14:47,595
This promotion throws into sharp relief

198
00:14:47,637 --> 00:14:50,598
that which I have not yet achieved.

199
00:14:53,059 --> 00:14:54,811
A marriage to a fine woman.

200
00:14:56,354 --> 00:14:59,023
You have become a fine woman, Elizabeth.

201
00:14:59,607 --> 00:15:00,983
I can't breathe.

202
00:15:01,067 --> 00:15:02,860
Yes, I...

203
00:15:02,944 --> 00:15:04,445
I'm a bit nervous myself.

204
00:15:07,323 --> 00:15:09,033
And then they made me their chief.

205
00:15:11,994 --> 00:15:13,037
Elizabeth?

206
00:15:15,748 --> 00:15:16,749
Elizabeth!

207
00:15:19,001 --> 00:15:21,712
The rocks!
Sir, it's a miracle she missed them!

208
00:15:24,215 --> 00:15:26,509
- Will you be saving her, then?
- I can't swim!

209
00:15:28,678 --> 00:15:30,680
Pearl of the King's Navy, you are!

210
00:15:30,721 --> 00:15:32,432
Do not lose these!

211
00:15:42,608 --> 00:15:45,278
[pulsates]

212
00:15:46,904 --> 00:15:48,114
What was that?

213
00:16:22,773 --> 00:16:24,400
[man] Make way!

214
00:16:30,948 --> 00:16:31,949
I got her!

215
00:16:33,326 --> 00:16:34,494
She's not breathing!

216
00:16:34,577 --> 00:16:35,578
Move!

217
00:16:38,581 --> 00:16:42,585
[gasping coughing]

218
00:16:42,668 --> 00:16:44,420
I never would've thought of that.

219
00:16:44,504 --> 00:16:46,756
Clearly you've never been to Singapore.

220
00:16:52,345 --> 00:16:53,971
Where did you get that?

221
00:16:56,182 --> 00:16:58,392
On your feet.

222
00:16:59,769 --> 00:17:01,020
[Swann] Elizabeth!

223
00:17:02,355 --> 00:17:04,357
- Are you all right?
- Yes, I'm fine.

224
00:17:09,320 --> 00:17:11,906
- Shoot him!
- Father! Commodore...

225
00:17:11,948 --> 00:17:13,991
...do you intend to kill my rescuer?

226
00:17:21,374 --> 00:17:23,167
I believe thanks are in order.

227
00:17:27,797 --> 00:17:30,633
Had a brush with the East India
Trading Company, did we?

228
00:17:30,675 --> 00:17:31,968
Pirate?

229
00:17:33,219 --> 00:17:34,512
Hang him.

230
00:17:34,595 --> 00:17:37,348
Keep your guns on him, men.
Gillette, fetch some irons.

231
00:17:38,599 --> 00:17:39,934
Well, well.

232
00:17:39,976 --> 00:17:42,478
Jack Sparrow, isn't it?

233
00:17:42,562 --> 00:17:45,189
Captain Jack Sparrow,
if you please, sir.

234
00:17:45,273 --> 00:17:47,149
Well, I don't see your ship...

235
00:17:47,191 --> 00:17:48,359
...captain.

236
00:17:48,442 --> 00:17:50,820
I'm in the market, as it were.

237
00:17:50,861 --> 00:17:52,863
He said he'd come to commandeer one.

238
00:17:52,947 --> 00:17:55,741
I told you he was telling the truth.
These are his, sir.

239
00:17:59,203 --> 00:18:02,331
No additional shots nor powder.

240
00:18:04,166 --> 00:18:06,002
A compass that doesn't point north.

241
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:13,676
And I half expected it
to be made of wood.

242
00:18:16,178 --> 00:18:19,098
You are, without doubt,
the worst pirate I've heard of.

243
00:18:20,099 --> 00:18:21,517
But you have heard of me.

244
00:18:24,478 --> 00:18:27,023
Commodore, I really must protest!

245
00:18:27,106 --> 00:18:28,691
Carefully, lieutenant.

246
00:18:28,733 --> 00:18:31,027
Pirate or not, this man saved my life!

247
00:18:31,068 --> 00:18:34,572
One good deed is not enough to redeem
a man of a lifetime of wickedness!

248
00:18:34,655 --> 00:18:36,365
But it seems enough to condemn him.

249
00:18:36,449 --> 00:18:37,908
Indeed.

250
00:18:39,452 --> 00:18:41,162
- Finally.
- [gasps]

251
00:18:41,203 --> 00:18:43,539
- [all gasp]
- Wait, don't shoot!

252
00:18:43,581 --> 00:18:44,915
I knew you'd warm up to me.

253
00:18:44,999 --> 00:18:47,793
Commodore Norrington,
my effects, please.

254
00:18:47,877 --> 00:18:49,545
And my hat.

255
00:18:50,171 --> 00:18:51,505
Commodore.

256
00:18:54,050 --> 00:18:57,386
- Elizabeth. It is Elizabeth, isn't it?
- It's Miss Swann.

257
00:18:57,428 --> 00:19:00,056
Miss Swann, if you'd be so kind.

258
00:19:00,097 --> 00:19:02,725
Come, dear, we don't have all day.

259
00:19:04,060 --> 00:19:05,478
Now, if you'll be very kind.

260
00:19:22,495 --> 00:19:23,913
Easy on the goods, darling.

261
00:19:25,331 --> 00:19:26,749
You're despicable.

262
00:19:26,832 --> 00:19:28,876
Sticks and stones, love.

263
00:19:28,918 --> 00:19:30,503
I saved your life, you save mine.

264
00:19:30,586 --> 00:19:31,587
We're square.

265
00:19:32,588 --> 00:19:33,798
Gentlemen...

266
00:19:33,881 --> 00:19:35,341
...my lady...

267
00:19:35,424 --> 00:19:36,165
...you will always remember this
as the day you almost caught...

268
00:19:36,175 --> 00:19:38,761
...you will always remember this
as the day you almost caught...

269
00:19:38,844 --> 00:19:41,263
...Captain Jack Sparrow!

270
00:19:57,822 --> 00:19:59,782
Whoa!

271
00:19:59,865 --> 00:20:01,325
Now, will you shoot him?

272
00:20:01,409 --> 00:20:03,077
Open fire!

273
00:20:04,829 --> 00:20:05,996
Ahh!

274
00:20:10,376 --> 00:20:11,794
Bum his heels!

275
00:20:20,720 --> 00:20:21,929
Take steady aim.

276
00:20:21,971 --> 00:20:23,305
[man] Fire!

277
00:20:24,181 --> 00:20:27,143
- [gunshots continue]
- [bullets ricochet]

278
00:20:27,226 --> 00:20:29,228
[man] Take cover, men!

279
00:20:29,311 --> 00:20:31,230
Gillette...

280
00:20:31,313 --> 00:20:34,150
...Mr Sparrow has a dawn
appointment with the gallows.

281
00:20:34,525 --> 00:20:36,527
I would hate for him to miss it.

282
00:20:40,531 --> 00:20:41,949
[man] Search upstairs!

283
00:20:43,284 --> 00:20:44,493
Look lively, men!

284
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:48,247
[chickens clucking]

285
00:21:10,561 --> 00:21:12,396
[snoring]

286
00:21:21,947 --> 00:21:24,325
[grunts]

287
00:21:24,366 --> 00:21:26,535
[snoring continues]

288
00:21:26,619 --> 00:21:27,995
Whoa!

289
00:21:46,514 --> 00:21:49,350
- [sizzling]
- [braying]

290
00:22:17,753 --> 00:22:19,880
Right where I left you.

291
00:22:26,428 --> 00:22:28,264
Not where I left you.

292
00:22:38,858 --> 00:22:40,693
You're the one they're hunting.

293
00:22:41,694 --> 00:22:42,862
The pirate!

294
00:22:43,612 --> 00:22:46,740
You seem somewhat familiar.
Have I threatened you before?

295
00:22:46,782 --> 00:22:49,451
I make a point of avoiding
familiarity with pirates.

296
00:22:49,535 --> 00:22:50,578
Ah...

297
00:22:50,619 --> 00:22:53,289
It would be a shame to put
a black mark on your record.

298
00:22:53,372 --> 00:22:54,874
So if you'll excuse me...

299
00:22:58,377 --> 00:23:00,546
Do you think this wise, boy?

300
00:23:01,505 --> 00:23:04,675
Crossing blades with a pirate?

301
00:23:04,758 --> 00:23:06,135
You threatened Miss Swarm.

302
00:23:09,179 --> 00:23:10,514
Only a little.

303
00:23:24,111 --> 00:23:27,281
You know what you're doing,
I'll give you that. Excellent form.

304
00:23:28,157 --> 00:23:29,867
But how's your footwork?

305
00:23:29,950 --> 00:23:32,036
If I step here...

306
00:23:33,412 --> 00:23:34,830
Very good.

307
00:23:34,872 --> 00:23:36,957
And now I step again.

308
00:23:41,670 --> 00:23:43,005
Ta.

309
00:24:02,900 --> 00:24:04,568
That is a wonderful trick.

310
00:24:05,861 --> 00:24:09,531
Except, once again,
you are between me and my way out.

311
00:24:09,615 --> 00:24:10,741
And now...

312
00:24:11,367 --> 00:24:12,785
...you have no weapon.

313
00:24:15,412 --> 00:24:17,706
[braying]

314
00:24:35,140 --> 00:24:36,767
Who makes all these?

315
00:24:38,227 --> 00:24:39,561
I do.

316
00:24:39,603 --> 00:24:41,897
And I practice with them...

317
00:24:42,439 --> 00:24:43,565
...three hours a day.

318
00:24:45,401 --> 00:24:47,569
You need to find yourself a girl, mate.

319
00:24:54,243 --> 00:24:57,162
Or... perhaps the reason
you practice three hours a day

320
00:24:57,246 --> 00:24:59,081
is that you already found one,

321
00:24:59,123 --> 00:25:02,751
and are otherwise incapable
of wooing said strumpet.

322
00:25:02,835 --> 00:25:05,254
You're not a eunuch, are you?

323
00:25:05,337 --> 00:25:08,298
I practice three hours a day
so that when I meet a pirate,

324
00:25:08,382 --> 00:25:09,758
I can kill him!

325
00:26:20,496 --> 00:26:21,747
[clanging]

326
00:26:27,002 --> 00:26:28,045
You cheated.

327
00:26:28,128 --> 00:26:29,379
Pirate.

328
00:26:29,463 --> 00:26:31,090
- [banging]
- [men groaning]

329
00:26:32,966 --> 00:26:35,010
- Move away!
- No.

330
00:26:35,052 --> 00:26:36,428
Please move?

331
00:26:36,512 --> 00:26:37,513
No!

332
00:26:37,554 --> 00:26:40,349
I cannot just step aside
and let you escape.

333
00:26:42,893 --> 00:26:44,895
This shot is not meant for you.

334
00:26:46,188 --> 00:26:48,023
[glass breaking]

335
00:26:48,065 --> 00:26:51,819
[banging, groaning continue]

336
00:26:55,239 --> 00:26:57,241
[man] There he is! Over here!

337
00:26:59,243 --> 00:27:01,203
Excellent work, Mr Brown.

338
00:27:02,204 --> 00:27:05,082
You've assisted in the capture
of a dangerous fugitive.

339
00:27:05,165 --> 00:27:07,459
Just doing my civic duty, sir.

340
00:27:08,460 --> 00:27:11,046
I trust you will always remember
that this is the day

341
00:27:11,088 --> 00:27:14,550
Captain Jack Sparrow almost escaped.

342
00:27:14,591 --> 00:27:16,343
Take him away.

343
00:27:20,639 --> 00:27:23,559
- [whistling] Come here, boy!
- Smell it?

344
00:27:23,600 --> 00:27:26,937
- Come here, boy!
- You want a nice, juicy bone?

345
00:27:27,020 --> 00:27:29,148
- Hey!
- Come here, boy!

346
00:27:29,231 --> 00:27:31,733
- Come here, boy!
- You can keep doing that forever.

347
00:27:31,817 --> 00:27:34,027
The dog is never going to move.

348
00:27:34,069 --> 00:27:38,365
Well, excuse us if we haven't resigned
ourselves to the gallows just yet!

349
00:27:39,408 --> 00:27:40,826
Come on!

350
00:27:45,080 --> 00:27:46,373
There you go, miss.

351
00:27:46,415 --> 00:27:49,209
It was a difficult day for you,
I'm sure.

352
00:27:49,251 --> 00:27:51,920
I suspected Commodore Norrington
would propose,

353
00:27:52,004 --> 00:27:54,590
but I must admit,
I wasn't entirely prepared for it.

354
00:27:54,673 --> 00:27:56,925
I meant you being
threatened by that pirate!

355
00:27:56,967 --> 00:27:58,218
Sounds terrifying!

356
00:27:58,969 --> 00:28:01,722
Oh... Yes, it was terrifying.

357
00:28:01,763 --> 00:28:03,765
But... the Commodore proposed!

358
00:28:03,849 --> 00:28:05,434
Fancy that.

359
00:28:05,517 --> 00:28:07,102
Now that's a smart match, miss,

360
00:28:07,186 --> 00:28:09,313
if it's not too bold to say.

361
00:28:09,396 --> 00:28:10,772
It is a smart match.

362
00:28:11,940 --> 00:28:13,734
He's a fine man.

363
00:28:15,027 --> 00:28:17,529
He's what any woman
should dream of marrying.

364
00:28:18,614 --> 00:28:20,741
Well, that Will Turner,

365
00:28:20,782 --> 00:28:22,951
he's a fine man too.

366
00:28:22,993 --> 00:28:24,786
That is too bold.

367
00:28:24,870 --> 00:28:26,955
Well, beggin' your pardon, miss.

368
00:28:26,997 --> 00:28:28,665
It was not my place.

369
00:29:17,714 --> 00:29:20,717
Has my daughter given
you an answer yet?

370
00:29:20,801 --> 00:29:22,511
No, she hasn't.

371
00:29:22,552 --> 00:29:24,888
Well, she has had a very trying day.

372
00:29:26,556 --> 00:29:28,725
Ghastly weather, don't you think?

373
00:29:28,809 --> 00:29:30,686
Bleak. Really bleak.

374
00:29:30,727 --> 00:29:32,396
[thudding in distance]

375
00:29:32,479 --> 00:29:33,480
What's that?

376
00:29:34,564 --> 00:29:36,441
Cannon fire!

377
00:29:37,818 --> 00:29:39,695
Return fire!

378
00:29:39,736 --> 00:29:42,781
- I know those guns!
- [cannon fire continues]

379
00:29:47,744 --> 00:29:49,746
It's the <i>Pearl!</i>

380
00:29:49,830 --> 00:29:51,540
<i>Black Pearl?</i>

381
00:29:54,042 --> 00:29:55,669
I've heard stories.

382
00:29:55,711 --> 00:29:59,715
She's been preying on ships and
settlements for near ten years.

383
00:29:59,798 --> 00:30:01,383
Never leaves any survivors.

384
00:30:01,466 --> 00:30:02,884
No survivors.

385
00:30:02,926 --> 00:30:05,762
Then where do the stories
come from, I wonder?

386
00:30:15,063 --> 00:30:16,815
Clear the dock!

387
00:30:17,607 --> 00:30:19,067
[shouts]

388
00:30:23,697 --> 00:30:26,950
[screaming]

389
00:30:30,370 --> 00:30:32,039
[crying] Mama!

390
00:30:38,628 --> 00:30:40,255
[man] Hoist your oars!

391
00:30:40,297 --> 00:30:42,466
[shouting]

392
00:30:42,549 --> 00:30:45,135
[yelling]

393
00:30:45,218 --> 00:30:47,512
Come on, you!

394
00:31:17,626 --> 00:31:19,086
[groans]

395
00:31:34,643 --> 00:31:35,936
[screams]

396
00:31:38,271 --> 00:31:40,107
[Norrington] Sight the muzzle flash.

397
00:31:40,148 --> 00:31:41,149
Aim for the flashes.

398
00:31:41,233 --> 00:31:43,318
I need a full spread, fore and aft.

399
00:31:43,360 --> 00:31:45,028
Mr Stevens, more cartridges!

400
00:31:45,904 --> 00:31:49,032
Governor!
Barricade yourself in my office.

401
00:31:49,991 --> 00:31:50,992
Good God!

402
00:31:51,034 --> 00:31:52,661
That's an order.

403
00:32:05,549 --> 00:32:06,967
[knock on door]

404
00:32:09,594 --> 00:32:11,888
- [knocking continues]
- Don't!

405
00:32:12,681 --> 00:32:13,849
Hello, chum.

406
00:32:14,099 --> 00:32:15,100
[shrieks]

407
00:32:18,103 --> 00:32:19,646
Up there! Go!

408
00:32:29,448 --> 00:32:32,075
Miss! They've come to kidnap you!

409
00:32:32,159 --> 00:32:34,703
- What?
- You're the governor's daughter!

410
00:32:34,786 --> 00:32:35,954
[pirate] In here!

411
00:32:36,037 --> 00:32:37,664
- [pounding]
- [gasping]

412
00:32:37,706 --> 00:32:41,960
They haven't seen you. Hide, and the
first chance you get, run to the fort!

413
00:32:51,470 --> 00:32:53,096
Got ya! Haven't I?

414
00:32:53,180 --> 00:32:55,140
[barking]

415
00:32:56,600 --> 00:33:00,103
[screaming] No! No! It's hot!

416
00:33:00,187 --> 00:33:02,063
- I'm burning!
- Come on!

417
00:33:03,231 --> 00:33:05,025
[screams]

418
00:33:06,526 --> 00:33:07,861
[man] Come on, me lads!

419
00:33:11,281 --> 00:33:12,574
[growls]

420
00:33:32,385 --> 00:33:33,845
[gasping]

421
00:33:35,096 --> 00:33:37,057
- Come out.
- [pirates grunting]

422
00:33:46,024 --> 00:33:48,860
We know you're here, poppet.

423
00:33:49,945 --> 00:33:51,112
Poppet.

424
00:33:51,196 --> 00:33:52,239
Come out...

425
00:33:53,156 --> 00:33:55,367
...and we promise we won't hurt you.

426
00:33:55,450 --> 00:33:56,701
Eh?

427
00:33:58,453 --> 00:34:00,455
We will find you, poppet.

428
00:34:01,498 --> 00:34:03,917
You've got something of ours,

429
00:34:03,959 --> 00:34:05,752
and it calls to us.

430
00:34:11,466 --> 00:34:13,969
The gold calls to us.

431
00:34:15,011 --> 00:34:16,179
[pirate 2] The gold.

432
00:34:22,310 --> 00:34:24,354
Hello, poppet.

433
00:34:24,896 --> 00:34:25,897
Parley!

434
00:34:26,606 --> 00:34:27,816
What?

435
00:34:27,857 --> 00:34:29,025
Parley.

436
00:34:29,109 --> 00:34:30,527
I invoke the right of parley.

437
00:34:30,610 --> 00:34:34,531
According to the code of Brethren, set
down by pirates Morgan and Bartholomew,

438
00:34:34,614 --> 00:34:37,701
- you have to take me to your captain.
- I know the code.

439
00:34:37,784 --> 00:34:40,495
If an adversary demands parley,
you can do them no harm

440
00:34:40,537 --> 00:34:43,331
- until the parley is complete.
- To blazes with the code!

441
00:34:43,415 --> 00:34:45,375
She wants to be taken to the captain.

442
00:34:46,876 --> 00:34:49,170
And she'll go, without a fuss.

443
00:34:50,213 --> 00:34:53,258
We must honour the code.

444
00:34:57,429 --> 00:34:59,681
[grunting]

445
00:34:59,723 --> 00:35:01,683
[grunting]

446
00:35:03,893 --> 00:35:05,270
Say goodbye!

447
00:35:09,983 --> 00:35:11,234
Goodbye.

448
00:35:15,363 --> 00:35:17,157
- Come on!
- Elizabeth!

449
00:35:18,658 --> 00:35:19,784
Well!

450
00:35:26,583 --> 00:35:28,168
Out of my way, scum!

451
00:35:29,210 --> 00:35:31,588
[laughing]

452
00:35:40,805 --> 00:35:43,725
My sympathies, friend.
You've no manner of luck at all.

453
00:35:43,767 --> 00:35:46,770
[prisoners chuckling]

454
00:36:03,787 --> 00:36:06,247
- [Jack whistling]
- [whimpers]

455
00:36:06,289 --> 00:36:09,501
Come on, doggy!
It's just you and me now.

456
00:36:09,584 --> 00:36:11,961
It's you and old Jack.
Come on.

457
00:36:12,045 --> 00:36:13,755
Come on. That's a boy!

458
00:36:13,797 --> 00:36:15,965
Good boy. Come get your bone!

459
00:36:16,049 --> 00:36:19,928
That's a good boy.
Come on, a bit closer, a bit closer.

460
00:36:20,011 --> 00:36:22,055
That's it! That's it, doggy!

461
00:36:22,097 --> 00:36:25,517
Come on, you filthy,
slimy, mangy cur!

462
00:36:25,600 --> 00:36:26,685
[door opens]

463
00:36:26,768 --> 00:36:28,436
Don't do that. No, no, no!

464
00:36:28,478 --> 00:36:30,146
I didn't mean it! I didn't...

465
00:36:30,230 --> 00:36:32,273
- [groans]
- [gunshot]

466
00:36:32,315 --> 00:36:36,945
- [clamouring]
- [chattering]

467
00:36:37,028 --> 00:36:38,571
This ain't the armoury!

468
00:36:40,281 --> 00:36:41,491
Well, well, well.

469
00:36:41,574 --> 00:36:44,452
Look what we have here, Twigg.

470
00:36:44,536 --> 00:36:46,621
Captain Jack Sparrow.

471
00:36:46,663 --> 00:36:47,706
[spits]

472
00:36:47,789 --> 00:36:49,958
[Twigg] Last time I saw you,

473
00:36:49,999 --> 00:36:51,793
you were all alone

474
00:36:51,876 --> 00:36:54,629
on a godforsaken island,

475
00:36:54,671 --> 00:36:56,881
shrinking into the distance.

476
00:36:56,965 --> 00:36:59,467
His fortunes aren't improved much.

477
00:36:59,551 --> 00:37:02,971
Worry about your own fortunes,
gentlemen.

478
00:37:03,012 --> 00:37:06,057
The deepest circle of hell
is reserved for betrayers

479
00:37:06,141 --> 00:37:07,684
and mutineers.

480
00:37:08,143 --> 00:37:09,978
[grunts]

481
00:37:11,813 --> 00:37:13,314
So there is a curse.

482
00:37:15,024 --> 00:37:16,401
That's interesting.

483
00:37:16,484 --> 00:37:18,737
You know nothing of hell.

484
00:37:27,412 --> 00:37:29,414
That's very interesting.

485
00:37:37,505 --> 00:37:39,591
[cannon fire]

486
00:37:52,854 --> 00:37:55,857
[clamouring]

487
00:38:02,030 --> 00:38:03,281
[monkey chittering]

488
00:38:04,866 --> 00:38:07,410
I didn't know we was takin' on captives.

489
00:38:07,494 --> 00:38:10,538
She's invoked the right of parley
with Captain Barbossa.

490
00:38:10,622 --> 00:38:14,459
- I am here to negotia...
- You will speak when spoken to!

491
00:38:15,460 --> 00:38:17,545
And ye will not lay a hand on those

492
00:38:17,587 --> 00:38:20,006
under the protection of parley.

493
00:38:20,632 --> 00:38:21,800
Aye, sir.

494
00:38:24,511 --> 00:38:26,429
My apologies, miss.

495
00:38:27,514 --> 00:38:28,848
Captain Barbossa,

496
00:38:28,890 --> 00:38:33,311
I am here to negotiate the cessation
of hostilities against Port Royal.

497
00:38:34,395 --> 00:38:38,441
A lot of long words in there, miss.
We are naught but humble pirates.

498
00:38:39,526 --> 00:38:41,110
What is it that you want?

499
00:38:41,194 --> 00:38:43,488
I want you to leave
and never come back.

500
00:38:43,571 --> 00:38:45,281
[all laughing]

501
00:38:45,949 --> 00:38:48,576
I'm disinclined
to acquiesce to your request.

502
00:38:50,161 --> 00:38:52,497
Means "no."

503
00:38:53,915 --> 00:38:54,916
Very well.

504
00:38:57,627 --> 00:38:59,504
I'll drop it.

505
00:38:59,587 --> 00:39:01,047
[chittering]

506
00:39:03,550 --> 00:39:08,179
Me holds are burstin' with swag!
That bit of shine matters to us?

507
00:39:08,263 --> 00:39:09,305
Why?

508
00:39:10,431 --> 00:39:12,725
It's what you've been searching for.

509
00:39:12,767 --> 00:39:14,435
I recognise the ship.

510
00:39:14,519 --> 00:39:17,397
I saw it eight years ago
on the crossing from England!

511
00:39:17,438 --> 00:39:18,606
Did you now?

512
00:39:21,609 --> 00:39:22,610
Fine.

513
00:39:23,611 --> 00:39:25,196
I suppose if it is worthless,

514
00:39:25,280 --> 00:39:27,115
then there's no point in me keeping it.

515
00:39:27,156 --> 00:39:28,449
- [all gasping]
- No!

516
00:39:34,038 --> 00:39:35,832
[chuckles]

517
00:39:39,377 --> 00:39:41,462
You have a name, missy?

518
00:39:42,589 --> 00:39:43,631
Elizabeth...

519
00:39:43,715 --> 00:39:45,049
...Turner.

520
00:39:46,175 --> 00:39:48,261
I'm a maid in the governor's household.

521
00:39:51,556 --> 00:39:52,974
Miss Turner!

522
00:39:54,183 --> 00:39:55,435
[all] Turner!

523
00:39:55,476 --> 00:39:56,895
Bootstrap!

524
00:40:00,940 --> 00:40:03,610
And how does a maid come
to own a trinket such as that?

525
00:40:03,651 --> 00:40:06,237
Family heirloom, perhaps?

526
00:40:06,321 --> 00:40:08,823
I didn't steal it,
if that's what you mean.

527
00:40:10,408 --> 00:40:13,494
Very well. You hand it over,
we'll put your town to our rudder,

528
00:40:13,578 --> 00:40:14,787
and ne'er return.

529
00:40:28,509 --> 00:40:29,510
Our bargain?

530
00:40:32,513 --> 00:40:34,349
Still the guns and stow 'em.

531
00:40:34,390 --> 00:40:37,226
Signal the men, set the flags
and make good to clear port.

532
00:40:37,310 --> 00:40:39,020
Wait! You have to take me to shore.

533
00:40:39,062 --> 00:40:41,689
According to the code of
the order of the Brethren...

534
00:40:41,773 --> 00:40:45,443
Your return to shore was not part
of our negotiations nor our agreements,

535
00:40:45,526 --> 00:40:46,694
so I must do nothin'.

536
00:40:46,778 --> 00:40:49,864
Secondly, you must be a pirate
for the pirate's code to apply,

537
00:40:49,906 --> 00:40:51,532
and you're not, and thirdly...

538
00:40:51,574 --> 00:40:54,327
...the code is more of what
you'd call a guideline,

539
00:40:54,369 --> 00:40:55,870
instead of actual rules.

540
00:40:55,912 --> 00:40:58,331
Welcome aboard the <i>Black Pearl,</i>

541
00:40:58,373 --> 00:40:59,874
Miss Turner.

542
00:41:03,002 --> 00:41:06,047
- [clucking]
- [horse neighing]

543
00:41:10,051 --> 00:41:11,260
[groans]

544
00:41:20,561 --> 00:41:22,981
They've taken her!
They've taken Elizabeth!

545
00:41:23,064 --> 00:41:25,149
Mr Murtogg, remove this man.

546
00:41:26,234 --> 00:41:28,319
We have to hunt them down!
We must save her!

547
00:41:28,403 --> 00:41:30,446
And where do you propose we start?

548
00:41:31,698 --> 00:41:35,368
If you have any information concerning
my daughter, please share it.

549
00:41:37,662 --> 00:41:39,414
[Murtogg] That Jack Sparrow!

550
00:41:39,497 --> 00:41:41,749
He talked about the <i>Black Pearl.</i>

551
00:41:41,791 --> 00:41:43,710
Mentioned it is more what he did.

552
00:41:45,294 --> 00:41:48,423
Ask him where it is! Make a deal
with him, he could lead us to it.

553
00:41:48,464 --> 00:41:49,966
No. [exhales]

554
00:41:50,049 --> 00:41:53,344
The pirates who invaded this fort
left Sparrow locked in his cell,

555
00:41:53,428 --> 00:41:56,431
ergo they are not his allies.

556
00:41:56,472 --> 00:41:59,475
Governor, we will establish
their most likely course...

557
00:41:59,559 --> 00:42:01,436
That's not good enough!

558
00:42:01,477 --> 00:42:03,438
Mr Turner...

559
00:42:03,479 --> 00:42:07,025
...you are not a military man,
you are not a sailor.

560
00:42:08,067 --> 00:42:09,444
You are a blacksmith.

561
00:42:09,485 --> 00:42:12,321
And this is not the moment
for rash actions!

562
00:42:14,615 --> 00:42:17,618
Do not make the mistake of thinking
you are the only man here

563
00:42:17,702 --> 00:42:19,203
who cares for Elizabeth.

564
00:42:22,165 --> 00:42:25,126
[rattling]

565
00:42:25,209 --> 00:42:26,961
Please...

566
00:42:27,045 --> 00:42:29,172
[door opens]

567
00:42:31,340 --> 00:42:32,550
You! Sparrow!

568
00:42:32,633 --> 00:42:33,634
Aye?

569
00:42:33,676 --> 00:42:36,304
You are familiar with that ship,
the <i>Black Pearl?</i>

570
00:42:36,345 --> 00:42:37,722
I've heard of it.

571
00:42:37,805 --> 00:42:39,140
Where does it make berth?

572
00:42:39,223 --> 00:42:40,475
Where does it make berth?

573
00:42:41,476 --> 00:42:43,436
Have you not heard the stories?

574
00:42:45,146 --> 00:42:47,106
Captain Barbossa

575
00:42:47,148 --> 00:42:48,900
and his crew of miscreants

576
00:42:48,983 --> 00:42:51,569
sail from the dreaded Isla de Muerte.

577
00:42:51,652 --> 00:42:54,447
It's an island that
cannot be found, except

578
00:42:54,489 --> 00:42:57,575
by those who already know where it is.

579
00:42:57,658 --> 00:42:59,327
The ship's real enough,

580
00:42:59,368 --> 00:43:02,830
therefore its anchorage must be
a real place. Where is it?

581
00:43:03,831 --> 00:43:04,999
Why ask me?

582
00:43:05,666 --> 00:43:07,251
Because you're a pirate.

583
00:43:07,335 --> 00:43:10,004
And you want to turn
pirate yourself. Is that it?

584
00:43:11,255 --> 00:43:12,256
Never!

585
00:43:16,010 --> 00:43:17,678
They took Miss Swann.

586
00:43:17,720 --> 00:43:19,555
Oh. So it is that you found a girl!

587
00:43:19,639 --> 00:43:21,432
I see.

588
00:43:21,516 --> 00:43:24,268
If you're intending to brave all,
hasten to her rescue,

589
00:43:24,352 --> 00:43:26,312
and so win fair lady's heart...

590
00:43:26,354 --> 00:43:28,981
...you'll have to do it alone, mate.

591
00:43:29,023 --> 00:43:31,109
I see no profit in it for me.

592
00:43:32,193 --> 00:43:33,444
I can get you out of here.

593
00:43:33,528 --> 00:43:35,196
How's that? The key's run off.

594
00:43:35,238 --> 00:43:36,864
I helped build these cells.

595
00:43:36,948 --> 00:43:39,700
These are half-pin barrel hinges.

596
00:43:40,993 --> 00:43:44,288
With the right leverage,
and the proper application of strength,

597
00:43:45,414 --> 00:43:46,833
the door will lift free.

598
00:43:49,210 --> 00:43:50,461
What's your name?

599
00:43:50,545 --> 00:43:52,463
Will Turner.

600
00:43:53,756 --> 00:43:56,092
That would be short for William,
I imagine.

601
00:43:56,175 --> 00:43:57,343
Good, strong name.

602
00:43:58,344 --> 00:44:00,263
No doubt named for your father?

603
00:44:01,889 --> 00:44:02,974
Yes.

604
00:44:03,057 --> 00:44:04,976
Uh-huh.

605
00:44:05,852 --> 00:44:07,186
Well, Mr Turner,

606
00:44:07,228 --> 00:44:08,437
I've changed me mind.

607
00:44:09,105 --> 00:44:12,108
If you spring me from this cell,
I swear, on pain of death,

608
00:44:12,191 --> 00:44:14,402
I shall take you to the <i>Black Pearl,</i>

609
00:44:14,443 --> 00:44:16,112
and your bonny lass.

610
00:44:16,195 --> 00:44:18,197
Do we have an accord?

611
00:44:21,701 --> 00:44:23,536
- Agreed.
- Agreed.

612
00:44:23,578 --> 00:44:24,745
Get me out.

613
00:44:28,249 --> 00:44:32,044
- Hurry! Someone will have heard that.
- Not without my effects.

614
00:44:38,634 --> 00:44:40,136
We're going to steal the ship?

615
00:44:41,929 --> 00:44:42,930
That ship?

616
00:44:43,014 --> 00:44:44,849
[Jack] Commandeer.

617
00:44:44,932 --> 00:44:47,185
We're going to commandeer that ship.

618
00:44:47,268 --> 00:44:48,352
Nautical term.

619
00:44:49,020 --> 00:44:51,105
One question about your business, boy,

620
00:44:51,189 --> 00:44:52,607
or there's no use going.

621
00:44:52,690 --> 00:44:54,192
This girl...

622
00:44:54,275 --> 00:44:56,986
...how far are you willing to go
to save her?

623
00:44:57,069 --> 00:44:58,404
I'd die for her.

624
00:44:58,446 --> 00:44:59,655
Oh, good.

625
00:44:59,739 --> 00:45:01,741
No worries then.

626
00:45:20,760 --> 00:45:23,304
This is either madness or brilliance.

627
00:45:24,096 --> 00:45:27,725
It's remarkable how often
those two traits coincide.

628
00:45:51,707 --> 00:45:54,669
[men chattering]

629
00:45:57,380 --> 00:46:01,175
Everyone stay calm!
We're taking over the ship.

630
00:46:01,259 --> 00:46:02,969
Aye! Avast!

631
00:46:03,344 --> 00:46:06,138
[all laughing]

632
00:46:06,180 --> 00:46:08,516
This ship cannot be crewed by two men.

633
00:46:09,392 --> 00:46:11,185
You'll never make it out of the bay.

634
00:46:11,227 --> 00:46:12,853
Son...

635
00:46:13,896 --> 00:46:16,732
...l'm Captain Jack Sparrow.

636
00:46:16,816 --> 00:46:18,359
Savvy?

637
00:46:21,862 --> 00:46:22,863
Commodore!

638
00:46:22,905 --> 00:46:25,533
[Gillette] Sir!
They're taking the <i>Dauntless!</i>

639
00:46:27,201 --> 00:46:28,286
Commodore!

640
00:46:28,369 --> 00:46:30,705
They're taking the ship!

641
00:46:31,455 --> 00:46:34,041
Sparrow and Turner!
They're taking the <i>Dauntless!</i>

642
00:46:34,083 --> 00:46:35,543
[Norrington] Rash, Turner.

643
00:46:35,626 --> 00:46:37,211
Too rash.

644
00:46:38,754 --> 00:46:42,967
That is, without doubt,
the worst pirate I have ever seen.

645
00:46:46,262 --> 00:46:47,555
Here they come.

646
00:46:52,393 --> 00:46:54,645
Bring her around!
Bring her around!

647
00:46:55,646 --> 00:46:59,942
[men shouting]

648
00:47:01,193 --> 00:47:04,363
Search every cabin, every hold,
down to the bilges.

649
00:47:17,501 --> 00:47:20,296
- [man] Check the aft!
- [man 2 indistinct]

650
00:47:20,379 --> 00:47:22,757
Sailors, back to the <i>Interceptor!</i>
Now!

651
00:47:22,798 --> 00:47:24,175
[man] Quickly, men

652
00:47:25,551 --> 00:47:26,844
Whoa!

653
00:47:29,263 --> 00:47:33,184
Thank you, commodore,
for getting us ready to make way.

654
00:47:33,267 --> 00:47:35,853
We'd have had a hard time
of it by ourselves.

655
00:47:39,106 --> 00:47:41,150
Set topsails and clear up this mess.

656
00:47:41,233 --> 00:47:43,778
With the wind a quarter astern,
we won't catch them!

657
00:47:43,861 --> 00:47:46,781
I don't need to. Just get them
in range of the long nines.

658
00:47:46,864 --> 00:47:48,949
Hands, come about! Run out the guns!

659
00:47:48,991 --> 00:47:50,368
[man] Bring out the guns!

660
00:47:50,451 --> 00:47:53,037
We are to fire on our own ship, sir?

661
00:47:53,120 --> 00:47:56,957
I'd rather see her at the bottom of the
ocean than in the hands of a pirate.

662
00:47:58,250 --> 00:48:01,587
Commodore! He's disabled
the rudder chain, sir.

663
00:48:05,299 --> 00:48:07,301
Abandon ship!

664
00:48:07,385 --> 00:48:09,595
[all screaming]

665
00:48:11,138 --> 00:48:13,557
[man] Let go the gear
and sheet home.

666
00:48:13,641 --> 00:48:16,102
That's got to be the best pirate
I've ever seen.

667
00:48:17,311 --> 00:48:19,939
So it would seem.

668
00:48:28,406 --> 00:48:30,491
[Will] When I was a lad,
living in England,

669
00:48:30,574 --> 00:48:32,451
my mother raised me by herself.

670
00:48:32,535 --> 00:48:34,495
After she died, I came out here,

671
00:48:34,578 --> 00:48:36,414
looking for my father.

672
00:48:37,873 --> 00:48:38,999
Is that so?

673
00:48:40,209 --> 00:48:41,752
My father,

674
00:48:41,836 --> 00:48:43,212
Bill Turner?

675
00:48:43,295 --> 00:48:46,882
At the jail, it was only after you
learned my name that you agreed to help.

676
00:48:46,966 --> 00:48:49,677
Since that's what I wanted,
I didn't press the matter.

677
00:48:49,718 --> 00:48:51,303
I'm not a simpleton, Jack.

678
00:48:51,345 --> 00:48:53,347
You knew my father.

679
00:48:55,599 --> 00:48:57,017
[sighs]

680
00:48:59,520 --> 00:49:00,563
I knew him.

681
00:49:00,646 --> 00:49:03,566
Probably one of the few
who knew him as William Turner.

682
00:49:03,649 --> 00:49:07,069
Everyone else just called him
"Bootstrap," or "Bootstrap Bill."

683
00:49:07,153 --> 00:49:08,154
Bootstrap?

684
00:49:09,155 --> 00:49:11,574
Good man.
Good pirate.

685
00:49:11,657 --> 00:49:13,742
I swear, you look just like him.

686
00:49:13,826 --> 00:49:14,869
It's not true.

687
00:49:14,910 --> 00:49:16,704
He was a merchant sailor.

688
00:49:16,787 --> 00:49:19,039
A good, respectable man
who obeyed the law.

689
00:49:19,123 --> 00:49:21,292
He was a bloody pirate, a scallywag.

690
00:49:22,668 --> 00:49:25,379
My father was not a pirate!

691
00:49:26,547 --> 00:49:28,549
Put it away, son.

692
00:49:28,632 --> 00:49:30,551
It's not worth you getting beat again.

693
00:49:30,634 --> 00:49:31,760
You didn't beat me.

694
00:49:31,844 --> 00:49:35,181
You ignored the rules of engagement.
In a fair fight, I'd kill you.

695
00:49:35,222 --> 00:49:38,058
That's not much incentive
for me to fight fair, is it?

696
00:49:40,603 --> 00:49:42,104
[grunts]

697
00:49:45,399 --> 00:49:48,652
Now as long as you're just
hanging there, pay attention.

698
00:49:48,736 --> 00:49:51,238
The only rules
that really matter are these:

699
00:49:51,322 --> 00:49:55,201
What a man can do,
and what a man can't do.

700
00:49:55,910 --> 00:49:57,077
For instance,

701
00:49:57,161 --> 00:50:00,289
you can accept that your father
was a pirate and a good man,

702
00:50:00,372 --> 00:50:01,415
or you can't.

703
00:50:01,457 --> 00:50:05,002
Pirate is in your blood, boy, so
you'll have to square with that someday.

704
00:50:05,878 --> 00:50:08,047
Now, me, for example.
I could let you drown,

705
00:50:08,088 --> 00:50:12,593
but I can't bring this ship into Tortuga
all by me onesies. Savvy?

706
00:50:12,927 --> 00:50:13,928
So...

707
00:50:17,515 --> 00:50:18,933
[grunts]

708
00:50:18,974 --> 00:50:22,311
Can you sail under
the command of a pirate?

709
00:50:23,562 --> 00:50:24,897
Or can you not?

710
00:50:27,608 --> 00:50:28,651
Tortuga?

711
00:50:28,734 --> 00:50:30,486
Tortuga.

712
00:50:43,415 --> 00:50:46,210
- [horse neighing]
- [man shouting]

713
00:50:46,293 --> 00:50:49,755
- [gunshots]
- [clamouring]

714
00:50:52,550 --> 00:50:54,969
[Jack] More importantly, it is indeed

715
00:50:55,010 --> 00:50:56,887
a sad life that has never
breathed deep

716
00:50:56,971 --> 00:51:00,140
the sweet, proliferous bouquet
that is Tortuga. Savvy?

717
00:51:01,892 --> 00:51:03,018
What do you think?

718
00:51:07,314 --> 00:51:08,399
It'll linger.

719
00:51:08,482 --> 00:51:12,486
I'll tell you, mate, if every town
in the world were like this one,

720
00:51:12,570 --> 00:51:15,030
no man would ever feel unwanted.

721
00:51:16,991 --> 00:51:18,075
Scarlett!

722
00:51:19,994 --> 00:51:21,328
Not sure I deserved that.

723
00:51:23,122 --> 00:51:24,290
Giselle!

724
00:51:24,331 --> 00:51:25,332
Who was she?

725
00:51:25,416 --> 00:51:26,417
What?

726
00:51:28,711 --> 00:51:30,004
I may have deserved that.

727
00:51:31,171 --> 00:51:32,172
[pigs squeal]

728
00:51:32,256 --> 00:51:35,384
Curse you for breathing,
you slack-jawed idiot!

729
00:51:35,467 --> 00:51:37,678
- [panting]
- [pigs snorting]

730
00:51:37,720 --> 00:51:39,847
Mother's love!

731
00:51:39,930 --> 00:51:40,931
Jack!

732
00:51:41,932 --> 00:51:45,060
You should know better than to
wake a man when he's sleepin'.

733
00:51:45,144 --> 00:51:49,023
- It's bad luck.
- Fortunately, I know how to counter it.

734
00:51:49,106 --> 00:51:52,401
The man who did the waking buys
the man who was sleeping a drink,

735
00:51:52,484 --> 00:51:55,904
and the man who was sleeping drinks
it while listening to a proposition

736
00:51:55,988 --> 00:51:57,698
from the man who did the waking.

737
00:51:59,867 --> 00:52:01,702
Aye, that'll about do it.

738
00:52:03,495 --> 00:52:05,539
- [grunts]
- [grunts]

739
00:52:06,540 --> 00:52:08,792
Blast! I'm already awake!

740
00:52:08,876 --> 00:52:10,252
That was for the smell.

741
00:52:13,547 --> 00:52:14,548
Eh...

742
00:52:14,632 --> 00:52:17,468
[clamouring]

743
00:52:19,303 --> 00:52:20,638
[glass breaking]

744
00:52:20,721 --> 00:52:22,222
Keep a sharp eye.

745
00:52:29,355 --> 00:52:30,439
Now...

746
00:52:30,522 --> 00:52:32,983
...what's the nature
of this venture of your'n?

747
00:52:34,818 --> 00:52:39,239
- I'm going after the <i>Black Pearl.</i>
- [coughing]

748
00:52:40,741 --> 00:52:42,242
I know where it's going to be,

749
00:52:42,284 --> 00:52:44,078
and I'm gonna take it.

750
00:52:45,120 --> 00:52:46,121
Jack,

751
00:52:46,205 --> 00:52:48,499
it's a fool's errand!

752
00:52:48,582 --> 00:52:51,919
Well, you know better than me
the tales of the <i>Black Pearl!</i>

753
00:52:51,960 --> 00:52:54,505
That's why I know
what Barbossa is up to.

754
00:52:55,089 --> 00:52:56,423
All I need is a crew.

755
00:52:57,132 --> 00:52:59,134
What I hear tell of Captain Barbossa,

756
00:52:59,218 --> 00:53:02,221
he's not a man to suffer fools,
nor strike a bargain with one!

757
00:53:02,262 --> 00:53:04,473
I'd say it's a good thing
I'm not a fool then.

758
00:53:04,556 --> 00:53:05,683
Prove me wrong!

759
00:53:06,350 --> 00:53:09,687
What makes you think Barbossa
will give up his ship to you?

760
00:53:09,770 --> 00:53:13,107
Let's just say
it's a matter of leverage, eh?

761
00:53:16,485 --> 00:53:17,778
Hm?

762
00:53:19,947 --> 00:53:20,989
Mm.

763
00:53:21,073 --> 00:53:22,449
Huh?

764
00:53:22,491 --> 00:53:23,617
Hm...

765
00:53:23,701 --> 00:53:24,702
Mm-hm-hm.

766
00:53:27,538 --> 00:53:29,289
[laughing]

767
00:53:29,331 --> 00:53:30,332
The kid?

768
00:53:31,917 --> 00:53:34,920
That is the child
of Bootstrap Bill Turner.

769
00:53:36,004 --> 00:53:38,465
His only child. Savvy?

770
00:53:38,549 --> 00:53:40,467
Is he now?

771
00:53:43,429 --> 00:53:45,806
Leverage, says you.

772
00:53:45,889 --> 00:53:48,475
I think I feel
a change in the wind, says I.

773
00:53:48,559 --> 00:53:50,310
- Mm.
- I'll find us a crew.

774
00:53:50,352 --> 00:53:53,272
There's bound to be some sailors
on this rock, crazy as you.

775
00:53:53,313 --> 00:53:55,691
One can only hope.

776
00:53:55,774 --> 00:53:58,527
- Take what you can!
- Give nothin' back!

777
00:54:23,385 --> 00:54:25,179
You'll be dining with the captain,

778
00:54:25,220 --> 00:54:27,598
and he requests you wear this.

779
00:54:28,557 --> 00:54:32,144
Tell the captain I'm "disinclined
to acquiesce to his request."

780
00:54:32,186 --> 00:54:33,228
[chuckles]

781
00:54:33,312 --> 00:54:35,564
He said you'd say that.

782
00:54:35,647 --> 00:54:38,025
He also said, if that be the case...

783
00:54:38,108 --> 00:54:39,860
...you'll be dining with the crew,

784
00:54:39,902 --> 00:54:41,737
- and you'll be naked.
- 

785
00:54:41,820 --> 00:54:43,864
[chuckling]

786
00:54:48,160 --> 00:54:49,286
Fine.

787
00:55:03,967 --> 00:55:05,886
[exhales]

788
00:55:05,928 --> 00:55:09,515
There's no need to stand on ceremony
no call to impress anyone.

789
00:55:09,556 --> 00:55:11,934
You must be hungry.

790
00:55:29,368 --> 00:55:30,577
Try the wine.

791
00:55:35,415 --> 00:55:38,418
And the apples. One of those next.

792
00:55:46,718 --> 00:55:48,387
It's poisoned.

793
00:55:48,428 --> 00:55:49,847
[chuckling]

794
00:55:49,930 --> 00:55:52,266
There would be no sense
to be killing you.

795
00:55:52,307 --> 00:55:55,769
Then release me. You have your trinket.
I'm of no further value to you.

796
00:55:59,773 --> 00:56:01,817
You don't know what this is,

797
00:56:01,900 --> 00:56:03,277
do you?

798
00:56:03,360 --> 00:56:05,612
It's a pirate medallion.

799
00:56:05,654 --> 00:56:07,739
This is Aztec gold.

800
00:56:08,615 --> 00:56:11,410
One of 882 identical pieces

801
00:56:11,451 --> 00:56:15,038
they delivered in a stone chest
to Cortes himself.

802
00:56:16,123 --> 00:56:20,335
Blood money paid to stem the slaughter
he wreaked upon them with his armies.

803
00:56:20,419 --> 00:56:24,256
But the greed of Cortés was insatiable.

804
00:56:24,298 --> 00:56:27,801
So the heathen gods
placed upon the gold...

805
00:56:29,678 --> 00:56:31,305
...a terrible curse.

806
00:56:32,931 --> 00:56:37,185
Any mortal that removes but
a single piece from that stone chest...

807
00:56:38,186 --> 00:56:40,647
...shall be punished for eternity.

808
00:56:42,941 --> 00:56:46,320
I hardly believe in ghost stories
anymore, Captain Barbossa.

809
00:56:46,403 --> 00:56:47,654
Aye.

810
00:56:48,447 --> 00:56:51,992
That's exactly what I thought
when we were first told the tale.

811
00:56:52,034 --> 00:56:54,953
Buried on an Isle of the Dead
what cannot be found,

812
00:56:54,995 --> 00:56:56,872
except for those who know where it is.

813
00:56:58,582 --> 00:56:59,917
Find it, we did.

814
00:57:01,585 --> 00:57:02,920
There be the chest.

815
00:57:03,003 --> 00:57:04,796
Inside be the gold.

816
00:57:05,756 --> 00:57:08,175
And we took 'em all!

817
00:57:08,216 --> 00:57:10,218
We spent 'em and traded 'em,

818
00:57:10,302 --> 00:57:11,970
and frittered 'em away

819
00:57:12,012 --> 00:57:14,765
on drink and food
and pleasurable company.

820
00:57:14,848 --> 00:57:16,850
The more we gave 'em away,

821
00:57:16,892 --> 00:57:19,561
the more we came to realise...

822
00:57:20,854 --> 00:57:23,023
...the drink would not satisfy.

823
00:57:24,274 --> 00:57:27,027
Food turned to ash in our mouths...

824
00:57:27,694 --> 00:57:30,280
...and all the pleasurable company
in the world

825
00:57:30,364 --> 00:57:32,366
could not slake our lust.

826
00:57:34,242 --> 00:57:37,037
We are cursed men, Miss Turner.

827
00:57:38,789 --> 00:57:41,458
Compelled by greed we were, but now...

828
00:57:41,541 --> 00:57:44,878
- [monkey chittering]
- …we are consumed by it.

829
00:57:56,056 --> 00:57:58,976
There is one way we can end our curse.

830
00:58:03,063 --> 00:58:06,024
All the scattered pieces
of the Aztec gold

831
00:58:06,066 --> 00:58:07,484
must be restored,

832
00:58:07,567 --> 00:58:09,987
and the blood repaid.

833
00:58:12,739 --> 00:58:14,116
Thanks to ye,

834
00:58:14,199 --> 00:58:16,326
we have the final piece.

835
00:58:18,370 --> 00:58:20,664
And the... blood to be repaid?

836
00:58:20,747 --> 00:58:23,250
That's why there's no sense
to be killing ya.

837
00:58:24,042 --> 00:58:25,043
Yet.

838
00:58:27,087 --> 00:58:28,588
Apple?

839
00:58:31,133 --> 00:58:33,593
- Ha-ha. Hah!
- [shrieks, panting]

840
00:58:33,635 --> 00:58:36,555
- [panting]
- Arrgh!

841
00:58:36,596 --> 00:58:38,140
[gasps] No!

842
00:58:39,391 --> 00:58:43,311
[Elizabeth gasping, panting]

843
00:58:45,439 --> 00:58:46,440
I'm curious.

844
00:58:46,523 --> 00:58:49,443
After killing me, what is it
you're planning on doing next?

845
00:58:56,033 --> 00:58:57,492
[shrieks]

846
00:58:59,244 --> 00:59:00,287
[grunting]

847
00:59:08,670 --> 00:59:11,006
[screaming]

848
00:59:18,472 --> 00:59:20,140
[screams]

849
00:59:21,349 --> 00:59:23,810
- [growls]
- [screams]

850
00:59:27,689 --> 00:59:30,317
[growling]

851
00:59:30,400 --> 00:59:31,860
[snarls]

852
00:59:33,653 --> 00:59:35,530
[grunts, gurgles]

853
00:59:35,614 --> 00:59:38,533
- [groans]
- [crackling]

854
00:59:38,617 --> 00:59:40,535
[growls]

855
00:59:45,332 --> 00:59:48,001
[panting]

856
00:59:48,085 --> 00:59:51,129
- [screams]
- [screeches]

857
00:59:53,006 --> 00:59:55,217
- [gasps]
- Look!

858
00:59:55,300 --> 00:59:58,220
The moonlight shows us
for what we really are.

859
00:59:59,012 --> 01:00:02,265
We are not among the living
and so we cannot die.

860
01:00:02,349 --> 01:00:04,017
But neither are we dead.

861
01:00:05,268 --> 01:00:09,064
For too long I've been parched of thirst
and unable to quench it.

862
01:00:09,147 --> 01:00:11,525
Too long I've been starvin' to death,

863
01:00:11,608 --> 01:00:13,235
and haven't died!

864
01:00:13,860 --> 01:00:15,654
I feel nothing.

865
01:00:16,446 --> 01:00:19,366
Not the wind on my face,
nor the spray of the sea...

866
01:00:20,784 --> 01:00:22,953
…nor the warmth of a woman's flesh.

867
01:00:23,954 --> 01:00:28,458
You best start believing
in ghost stories, Miss Turner.

868
01:00:28,542 --> 01:00:29,543
You're in one!

869
01:00:33,880 --> 01:00:36,716
[gurgling]

870
01:00:36,800 --> 01:00:38,885
- [dripping]
- [gasps]

871
01:00:45,559 --> 01:00:48,562
- [laughing]
- [all laugh]

872
01:00:48,603 --> 01:00:50,564
What are you looking at?
Back to work!

873
01:00:50,605 --> 01:00:52,816
[murmuring]

874
01:00:59,781 --> 01:01:01,449
[Gibbs] Feast your eyes, captain.

875
01:01:01,533 --> 01:01:04,452
All of them,
faithful hands before the mast.

876
01:01:04,536 --> 01:01:07,747
Every man worth his salt...

877
01:01:07,789 --> 01:01:09,833
...and crazy to boot.

878
01:01:09,916 --> 01:01:12,752
So this is your able-bodied crew?

879
01:01:18,592 --> 01:01:19,593
You, sailor!

880
01:01:19,676 --> 01:01:21,052
Cotton, sir.

881
01:01:21,094 --> 01:01:22,888
Mr Cotton.

882
01:01:22,929 --> 01:01:26,266
Do you have the courage and fortitude
to follow orders and stay true

883
01:01:26,349 --> 01:01:27,934
in the face of danger and death?

884
01:01:27,976 --> 01:01:29,686
Mr Cotton!

885
01:01:29,769 --> 01:01:30,896
Answer, man!

886
01:01:30,937 --> 01:01:32,355
He's a mute, sir.

887
01:01:32,439 --> 01:01:34,149
Poor devil had his tongue cut out.

888
01:01:34,232 --> 01:01:36,276
So he trained the parrot
to talk for him.

889
01:01:36,359 --> 01:01:38,236
No one's yet figured how.

890
01:01:41,448 --> 01:01:43,074
Mr Cotton's parrot.

891
01:01:44,075 --> 01:01:45,577
Same question.

892
01:01:45,619 --> 01:01:48,371
[squawks] Wind in your sails.
Wind in your sails.

893
01:01:49,497 --> 01:01:51,583
Mostly, we figure that means "yes."

894
01:01:51,625 --> 01:01:53,126
Of course it does.

895
01:01:53,210 --> 01:01:54,211
Satisfied?

896
01:01:55,170 --> 01:01:57,172
Well, you've proved they're mad!

897
01:01:57,255 --> 01:01:59,132
[woman] And what's the benefit for us?

898
01:02:09,643 --> 01:02:10,727
Anamaria!

899
01:02:12,646 --> 01:02:14,981
I suppose you didn't deserve
that one, either.

900
01:02:15,065 --> 01:02:16,983
No, that one I deserved.

901
01:02:17,025 --> 01:02:18,777
You stole my boat!

902
01:02:18,818 --> 01:02:19,903
Actually...

903
01:02:21,988 --> 01:02:24,366
Borrowed. Borrowed, without permission,

904
01:02:24,449 --> 01:02:27,035
but with every intention
of bringing it back to you.

905
01:02:27,118 --> 01:02:28,536
But you didn't!

906
01:02:28,620 --> 01:02:29,996
You'll get another one!

907
01:02:31,373 --> 01:02:32,374
I will!

908
01:02:32,457 --> 01:02:33,833
A better one.

909
01:02:33,917 --> 01:02:35,835
A better one!

910
01:02:35,919 --> 01:02:37,504
- That one!
- What one?

911
01:02:40,215 --> 01:02:41,383
That one?

912
01:02:44,844 --> 01:02:46,554
Aye. That one.

913
01:02:46,638 --> 01:02:48,223
- What say you?
- Aye!

914
01:02:48,306 --> 01:02:49,683
Aye!

915
01:02:49,766 --> 01:02:51,768
[parrot] Anchors away!

916
01:02:51,851 --> 01:02:54,062
No, no, no, no, no!
It's frightful bad luck

917
01:02:54,145 --> 01:02:55,647
to bring a woman aboard, sir.

918
01:02:55,689 --> 01:02:58,358
It'll be far worse not to have her.

919
01:03:02,237 --> 01:03:04,864
[thunderclap]

920
01:03:04,948 --> 01:03:07,200
[wind gusting]

921
01:03:23,383 --> 01:03:25,677
[creaking]

922
01:03:32,058 --> 01:03:35,103
How can we sail to an island
that nobody can find,

923
01:03:35,186 --> 01:03:37,647
with a compass that doesn't work?

924
01:03:37,731 --> 01:03:39,691
Aye, the compass doesn't point north,

925
01:03:39,733 --> 01:03:42,569
but we're not trying
to find north, are we?

926
01:03:53,246 --> 01:03:55,623
We should drop canvas, sir.

927
01:03:55,707 --> 01:03:57,751
She can hold a bit longer.

928
01:03:59,961 --> 01:04:03,506
What's in your head that's put you
in such a fine mood, captain?

929
01:04:03,590 --> 01:04:05,592
We're catching up.

930
01:04:16,853 --> 01:04:18,646
[door opens]

931
01:04:20,607 --> 01:04:22,609
Time to go, poppet.

932
01:04:22,692 --> 01:04:27,947
[grunting]

933
01:04:42,087 --> 01:04:44,214
[chittering]

934
01:05:12,158 --> 01:05:16,079
[creaking]

935
01:05:18,164 --> 01:05:22,585
[parrot] Dead men tell no tales...

936
01:05:25,130 --> 01:05:27,799
Puts a chill in the bones,
how many honest sailors

937
01:05:27,841 --> 01:05:29,676
have been claimed by this passage.

938
01:05:45,150 --> 01:05:47,527
How is it that Jack
came by that compass?

939
01:05:47,569 --> 01:05:50,780
Not a lot's known about Jack Sparrow
'fore he showed up in Tortuga

940
01:05:50,864 --> 01:05:53,533
with a mind to go after
the treasure of Isla de Muerte.

941
01:05:53,616 --> 01:05:54,868
That was before I met him,

942
01:05:54,951 --> 01:05:57,120
back when he was captain
of the <i>Black Pearl.</i>

943
01:05:57,996 --> 01:05:58,997
What?

944
01:06:02,667 --> 01:06:04,127
He failed to mention that.

945
01:06:04,210 --> 01:06:06,463
He plays things closer to the vest now.

946
01:06:06,546 --> 01:06:08,631
And a hard-learned lesson it was.

947
01:06:08,715 --> 01:06:11,593
Three days out on the venture,
the first mate says,

948
01:06:11,676 --> 01:06:14,762
"Everything's an equal share.
That should mean the location

949
01:06:14,846 --> 01:06:18,224
of the treasure too,"
so Jack gives up the bearings.

950
01:06:18,391 --> 01:06:20,560
That night, there was a mutiny.

951
01:06:21,603 --> 01:06:24,272
They marooned Jack on an island
and left him to die.

952
01:06:24,355 --> 01:06:27,025
But not before he'd
gone mad with the heat.

953
01:06:28,735 --> 01:06:30,403
Ah...

954
01:06:31,112 --> 01:06:33,531
So that's the reason for all the...

955
01:06:35,575 --> 01:06:37,285
Reason's got nothing to do with it.

956
01:06:38,244 --> 01:06:40,413
Now, Will, when a pirate's marooned,

957
01:06:40,497 --> 01:06:43,249
he's given a pistol with a single shot.
One shot...

958
01:06:43,291 --> 01:06:46,628
Well, that won't do much good hunting,
nor to be rescued.

959
01:06:46,711 --> 01:06:49,923
But after three weeks
of a starving belly and thirst,

960
01:06:49,964 --> 01:06:53,343
that pistol starts to look
real friendly.

961
01:06:53,426 --> 01:06:55,428
But Jack, he escaped the island,

962
01:06:55,512 --> 01:06:57,096
and still has that single shot.

963
01:06:57,180 --> 01:06:59,766
Oh, he won't use it, though,
save on one man.

964
01:07:00,767 --> 01:07:02,810
His mutinous first mate.

965
01:07:02,894 --> 01:07:04,854
- Barbossa.
- Aye.

966
01:07:06,105 --> 01:07:09,067
- How did Jack get off the island?
- Well, I'll tell ye.

967
01:07:09,108 --> 01:07:11,236
He waded out into the shallows,

968
01:07:11,277 --> 01:07:13,863
and he waited there three days
and three nights,

969
01:07:13,947 --> 01:07:17,784
till all manner of sea creatures
came acclimated to his presence.

970
01:07:18,785 --> 01:07:20,328
And on the fourth morning,

971
01:07:20,411 --> 01:07:24,541
he roped a couple of sea turtles,
lashed them together and made a raft.

972
01:07:26,793 --> 01:07:29,212
- He roped a couple of sea turtles.
- Aye.

973
01:07:29,295 --> 01:07:30,588
Sea turtles!

974
01:07:32,840 --> 01:07:34,842
What did he use for rope?

975
01:07:39,806 --> 01:07:41,391
Human hair.

976
01:07:42,392 --> 01:07:43,810
From my back.

977
01:07:44,978 --> 01:07:46,354
Let go the anchor!

978
01:07:46,437 --> 01:07:48,815
[all] Lower the anchor line!

979
01:07:48,898 --> 01:07:51,317
Young Mr Turner and I are to go ashore.

980
01:07:51,943 --> 01:07:53,069
Captain.

981
01:07:53,152 --> 01:07:54,862
What if the worst should happen?

982
01:07:55,738 --> 01:07:58,241
- Keep to the code.
- Aye. The code.

983
01:08:00,118 --> 01:08:01,369
[splash]

984
01:08:01,452 --> 01:08:03,663
[laughing]

985
01:08:04,831 --> 01:08:07,458
[man shouting indistinct]

986
01:08:07,500 --> 01:08:10,003
[clatter]

987
01:08:24,058 --> 01:08:25,226
Move.

988
01:08:25,310 --> 01:08:27,312
Ten years of hoarding swag!

989
01:08:27,353 --> 01:08:29,856
And now we finally get to spend it!

990
01:08:29,939 --> 01:08:32,650
[cackling]

991
01:08:32,692 --> 01:08:33,693
Oh.

992
01:08:37,196 --> 01:08:39,991
Once we're quit of the curse,
we'll be rich men...

993
01:08:40,700 --> 01:08:44,412
...and you can buy an eye what
actually fits and is made of glass.

994
01:08:44,495 --> 01:08:47,415
This one does splinter
something terrible!

995
01:08:47,498 --> 01:08:49,709
- [squeaking]
- Stop rubbing it!

996
01:08:50,835 --> 01:08:51,961
Oh!

997
01:08:53,921 --> 01:08:55,548
[groans]

998
01:09:09,354 --> 01:09:12,398
What code is Gibbs to keep to
if the worst should happen?

999
01:09:12,440 --> 01:09:14,734
The pirates' code.

1000
01:09:14,817 --> 01:09:16,235
Any man who falls behind...

1001
01:09:16,277 --> 01:09:18,613
…is left behind.

1002
01:09:19,947 --> 01:09:22,241
No heroes amongst thieves, eh?

1003
01:09:22,950 --> 01:09:26,037
You know, for having
such a bleak outlook on pirates,

1004
01:09:26,079 --> 01:09:28,998
you're well on your way
to becoming one.

1005
01:09:29,499 --> 01:09:31,084
Sprung a man from jail...

1006
01:09:32,418 --> 01:09:34,921
...commandeered a ship of the fleet,

1007
01:09:34,962 --> 01:09:37,507
sailed with a buccaneer crew
out of Tortuga...

1008
01:09:39,676 --> 01:09:42,929
...and you're completely
obsessed with treasure!

1009
01:09:45,682 --> 01:09:46,808
That's not true.

1010
01:09:47,517 --> 01:09:49,268
I am not obsessed with treasure.

1011
01:09:56,484 --> 01:09:59,237
Not all treasure
is silver and gold, mate.

1012
01:09:59,278 --> 01:10:01,322
[Barbossa] Gentlemen, the time has come!

1013
01:10:01,406 --> 01:10:02,615
[pirates] Hurrah!

1014
01:10:02,699 --> 01:10:04,826
Salvation is nigh!

1015
01:10:04,909 --> 01:10:06,327
[all] Yeah!

1016
01:10:06,411 --> 01:10:09,122
- [Barbossa] Our torment is near an end!
- Elizabeth.

1017
01:10:09,789 --> 01:10:12,667
[Barbossa] For ten years,
we've been tested and tried,

1018
01:10:12,750 --> 01:10:14,377
and each man-jack of you here

1019
01:10:14,460 --> 01:10:17,463
has proved his mettle 100 times over.

1020
01:10:17,505 --> 01:10:19,799
And 100 times again!

1021
01:10:19,841 --> 01:10:21,926
[all] Yeah!

1022
01:10:21,968 --> 01:10:23,553
Suffered, I have!

1023
01:10:24,303 --> 01:10:26,139
Punished, we were,

1024
01:10:26,180 --> 01:10:27,724
the lot of us,

1025
01:10:27,807 --> 01:10:31,144
disproportionate to our crime!

1026
01:10:31,227 --> 01:10:33,020
Right!

1027
01:10:33,104 --> 01:10:34,313
Here it is!

1028
01:10:37,984 --> 01:10:41,612
The cursed treasure of Cortes himself.

1029
01:10:43,614 --> 01:10:46,159
Every last piece that went astray,

1030
01:10:46,200 --> 01:10:47,952
we have returned.

1031
01:10:47,994 --> 01:10:49,704
Save for this!

1032
01:10:49,787 --> 01:10:51,205
- [all] Yeah!
- Jack!

1033
01:10:51,289 --> 01:10:53,916
- Not yet!
- [chittering]

1034
01:10:54,000 --> 01:10:56,502
We'll wait for the opportune moment.

1035
01:10:56,586 --> 01:10:59,338
[Barbossa] ...despairing
of ever finding the lass.

1036
01:10:59,380 --> 01:11:01,215
When's that?

1037
01:11:01,299 --> 01:11:04,010
When it's of greatest profit to you?

1038
01:11:04,051 --> 01:11:05,386
May I ask you something?

1039
01:11:06,763 --> 01:11:09,098
Have I ever given you
reason not to trust me?

1040
01:11:10,475 --> 01:11:11,476
Do us a favour.

1041
01:11:11,517 --> 01:11:13,644
I know it's difficult for you,

1042
01:11:13,686 --> 01:11:15,730
but please, stay here,

1043
01:11:15,813 --> 01:11:18,691
and try not to do anything stupid.

1044
01:11:21,360 --> 01:11:23,863
And who among us
has paid the blood sacrifice

1045
01:11:23,946 --> 01:11:26,199
- owed to the heathen gods?
- [all] Aye!

1046
01:11:26,282 --> 01:11:29,118
And whose blood must yet be paid?

1047
01:11:29,202 --> 01:11:30,870
[all] Hers!

1048
01:11:33,039 --> 01:11:37,627
You know the first thing I'm going
to do after the curse is lifted?

1049
01:11:37,710 --> 01:11:39,045
[chuckling]

1050
01:11:39,962 --> 01:11:43,382
Eat a whole bushel of apples!

1051
01:11:43,466 --> 01:11:44,550
[panting]

1052
01:11:44,592 --> 01:11:48,054
[chanting grunting]

1053
01:11:51,140 --> 01:11:53,142
Begun by blood,

1054
01:11:53,226 --> 01:11:55,228
by blood undone.

1055
01:11:59,690 --> 01:12:00,733
Sorry, Jack.

1056
01:12:00,817 --> 01:12:03,361
I'm not going to be your leverage.

1057
01:12:08,825 --> 01:12:11,244
[gasps]

1058
01:12:12,578 --> 01:12:14,747
That's it?

1059
01:12:14,789 --> 01:12:16,457
Waste not.

1060
01:12:20,253 --> 01:12:21,254
[chanting stops]

1061
01:12:54,453 --> 01:12:55,788
Did it work?

1062
01:12:55,830 --> 01:12:58,708
- I don't feel no different.
- How do we tell?

1063
01:13:01,919 --> 01:13:04,005
[all gasp]

1064
01:13:05,798 --> 01:13:07,300
You're not dead!

1065
01:13:08,342 --> 01:13:10,845
No. [chuckling]

1066
01:13:10,928 --> 01:13:12,263
He shot me!

1067
01:13:12,305 --> 01:13:15,850
It didn't work!
The curse is still upon us!

1068
01:13:20,938 --> 01:13:23,399
You! Maid! Your father,
what was his name?

1069
01:13:23,482 --> 01:13:25,735
Was your father William Turner?

1070
01:13:26,068 --> 01:13:27,320
No.

1071
01:13:27,361 --> 01:13:30,865
Where's his child? The child that sailed
from England eight years ago?

1072
01:13:30,948 --> 01:13:33,993
The child in whose veins flows
the blood of William Turner?

1073
01:13:34,076 --> 01:13:35,328
Where?

1074
01:13:41,709 --> 01:13:42,877
You two!

1075
01:13:42,960 --> 01:13:43,961
[gasps]

1076
01:13:44,003 --> 01:13:46,088
- You brought us the wrong person!
- Yeah!

1077
01:13:47,048 --> 01:13:48,049
No!

1078
01:13:48,799 --> 01:13:51,510
She had the medallion!
She's the proper age!

1079
01:13:51,594 --> 01:13:54,221
[man] She said her name
was Turner. You heard her!

1080
01:13:54,305 --> 01:13:56,015
[pirates grumbling]

1081
01:13:56,098 --> 01:13:58,768
- [man] I think she lied to us!
- [pirates] Yeah!

1082
01:14:00,019 --> 01:14:02,355
You brought us here for nothing!

1083
01:14:02,396 --> 01:14:06,525
I won't take questionin' or second
guesses, not from you, Mr Twigg!

1084
01:14:06,567 --> 01:14:10,863
Who's to blame him? Every decision
you made has led us from bad to worse!

1085
01:14:13,074 --> 01:14:15,660
It was you who sent
Bootstrap to the depths!

1086
01:14:15,701 --> 01:14:16,702
[all] Yeah!

1087
01:14:19,497 --> 01:14:22,083
And it's you who brought us
here in the first place!

1088
01:14:23,876 --> 01:14:26,545
If any coward here dare challenge me,
let him speak!

1089
01:14:28,839 --> 01:14:30,758
I say, we cut her throat,

1090
01:14:30,841 --> 01:14:32,468
and spill all her blood!

1091
01:14:32,551 --> 01:14:33,552
Just in case.

1092
01:14:33,594 --> 01:14:35,054
- Yeah!
- Yeah!

1093
01:14:35,137 --> 01:14:37,682
- [all] Yeah!
- [monkey chittering]

1094
01:14:43,646 --> 01:14:44,897
The medallion!

1095
01:14:44,939 --> 01:14:46,232
She's taken it!

1096
01:14:46,273 --> 01:14:50,778
Get after her,
you feckless pack of ingrates!

1097
01:14:50,861 --> 01:14:53,656
[pirates shouting]

1098
01:14:56,367 --> 01:14:59,370
- Where's the oars?
- There's no oars!

1099
01:14:59,412 --> 01:15:02,248
The oars have gone missing!
Find them!

1100
01:15:11,340 --> 01:15:13,092
You!

1101
01:15:14,427 --> 01:15:16,095
You're supposed to be dead!

1102
01:15:16,137 --> 01:15:17,471
Am I not?

1103
01:15:19,432 --> 01:15:20,433
Oh.

1104
01:15:21,809 --> 01:15:23,269
[gun cocks]

1105
01:15:24,687 --> 01:15:26,188
[gun cocks]

1106
01:15:27,523 --> 01:15:28,983
Puh-Ia-Iem.

1107
01:15:30,359 --> 01:15:32,611
Puh-Ia-Iie-Iay-Iool.

1108
01:15:35,197 --> 01:15:36,824
Pah-Iee-nee...

1109
01:15:36,907 --> 01:15:39,660
...parsnip... par-sley...

1110
01:15:39,744 --> 01:15:41,746
...par... partner, pardoner...

1111
01:15:41,787 --> 01:15:42,788
Parley?

1112
01:15:42,872 --> 01:15:44,707
That's the one! Parley!

1113
01:15:45,458 --> 01:15:46,459
[Jack] Parley!

1114
01:15:46,500 --> 01:15:47,793
Parley?!

1115
01:15:49,045 --> 01:15:52,840
Damn to the depths whatever
muttonhead thought up parley!

1116
01:15:54,467 --> 01:15:56,761
That would be the French.

1117
01:16:01,807 --> 01:16:03,768
[splashing]

1118
01:16:03,809 --> 01:16:06,645
[gasps]

1119
01:16:08,564 --> 01:16:09,774
Not more pirates!

1120
01:16:09,815 --> 01:16:11,859
Welcome aboard, Miss Elizabeth.

1121
01:16:12,818 --> 01:16:14,028
Mr Gibbs?

1122
01:16:14,737 --> 01:16:16,030
Hey, boy, where be Jack?

1123
01:16:17,156 --> 01:16:19,658
Jack? Jack Sparrow?

1124
01:16:20,910 --> 01:16:22,411
He fell behind.

1125
01:16:24,163 --> 01:16:26,123
[parrot squawking]

1126
01:16:29,960 --> 01:16:31,504
Keep to the code!

1127
01:16:32,755 --> 01:16:35,549
[Anamaria] Weigh anchor!
Hoist the sails!

1128
01:16:35,633 --> 01:16:37,301
Split-quick, you dibbies!

1129
01:16:43,516 --> 01:16:46,560
How the blazes
did you get off that island?

1130
01:16:47,937 --> 01:16:51,398
When you marooned me on
that godforsaken spit of land,

1131
01:16:51,482 --> 01:16:53,859
you forgot one
very important thing, mate.

1132
01:16:55,444 --> 01:16:57,863
I'm Captain Jack Sparrow.

1133
01:16:57,905 --> 01:17:01,534
Ah, well, I won't be
making that mistake...

1134
01:17:01,575 --> 01:17:02,785
…again.

1135
01:17:03,577 --> 01:17:07,039
Gents, you all remember
Captain Jack Sparrow?

1136
01:17:07,123 --> 01:17:08,332
[all] Aye.

1137
01:17:09,083 --> 01:17:10,084
Kill him.

1138
01:17:10,167 --> 01:17:11,210
[guns cocking]

1139
01:17:11,252 --> 01:17:13,921
The girl's blood didn't work, did it?

1140
01:17:16,590 --> 01:17:17,758
Hold your fire!

1141
01:17:19,260 --> 01:17:20,261
[grunts]

1142
01:17:24,390 --> 01:17:26,934
You know whose blood we need?

1143
01:17:28,644 --> 01:17:30,521
I know whose blood you need.

1144
01:17:37,653 --> 01:17:40,239
What sort of a man
trades a man's life for a ship?

1145
01:17:40,322 --> 01:17:41,574
A pirate.

1146
01:17:42,741 --> 01:17:44,076
Here.

1147
01:17:44,160 --> 01:17:45,870
Let me.

1148
01:17:45,911 --> 01:17:47,413
Thank you.

1149
01:17:48,789 --> 01:17:51,375
You said you gave Barbossa
my name as yours.

1150
01:17:53,252 --> 01:17:54,253
Why?

1151
01:17:57,590 --> 01:17:58,883
I don't know.

1152
01:17:59,508 --> 01:18:00,759
[winces, gasps]

1153
01:18:00,843 --> 01:18:03,053
I'm sorry. A blacksmith's hands.

1154
01:18:03,095 --> 01:18:07,683
- I know they're rough.
- No... I mean, yes, they are, but...

1155
01:18:10,144 --> 01:18:11,937
But don't stop.

1156
01:18:20,446 --> 01:18:21,864
Elizabeth!

1157
01:18:37,796 --> 01:18:39,131
It's yours.

1158
01:18:43,552 --> 01:18:46,972
I thought I'd lost it
the day they rescued me.

1159
01:18:47,014 --> 01:18:48,474
It was a gift from my father.

1160
01:18:48,515 --> 01:18:50,643
He sent it to me.

1161
01:18:56,315 --> 01:18:57,858
Why did you take it?

1162
01:18:59,985 --> 01:19:02,738
Because I was afraid
that you were a pirate.

1163
01:19:04,323 --> 01:19:06,116
That would've been awful.

1164
01:19:09,578 --> 01:19:11,372
It wasn't your blood they needed.

1165
01:19:14,166 --> 01:19:16,418
It was my father's blood.

1166
01:19:18,879 --> 01:19:21,465
My blood.

1167
01:19:26,387 --> 01:19:27,763
The blood of a pirate.

1168
01:19:27,846 --> 01:19:29,974
Will, I'm so sorry.
Please forgive me.

1169
01:19:43,320 --> 01:19:46,949
So you expect to leave me standin' on
some beach, with nothing but a name

1170
01:19:47,032 --> 01:19:52,371
and your word it's the one I need,
and watch you sail away in my ship?

1171
01:19:52,454 --> 01:19:53,622
No.

1172
01:19:53,706 --> 01:19:57,835
I expect to leave you standing on some
beach with absolutely no name at all,

1173
01:19:57,876 --> 01:19:59,962
watching me sail away on my ship,

1174
01:20:00,045 --> 01:20:02,923
and then I'll shout
the name back to you.

1175
01:20:03,007 --> 01:20:04,341
Savvy?

1176
01:20:04,383 --> 01:20:07,428
That still leaves the problem
of me standing on some beach,

1177
01:20:07,511 --> 01:20:11,348
with naught but a name and your word
it's the one I need.

1178
01:20:12,391 --> 01:20:13,726
Of the two of us,

1179
01:20:13,809 --> 01:20:17,604
I am the only one who
hasn't committed mutiny.

1180
01:20:17,688 --> 01:20:21,692
Therefore, my word is
the one we'll be trusting.

1181
01:20:21,734 --> 01:20:23,485
- Although...
- [monkey chitters]

1182
01:20:23,569 --> 01:20:26,196
I suppose I should be thanking you
because, in fact,

1183
01:20:26,238 --> 01:20:28,532
if you hadn't betrayed me
and left me to die,

1184
01:20:29,575 --> 01:20:33,871
I would have an equal share
in that curse, same as you.

1185
01:20:33,912 --> 01:20:35,289
Funny ol' world, isn't it?

1186
01:20:35,372 --> 01:20:36,707
Hm.

1187
01:20:39,293 --> 01:20:41,795
Captain! We're coming up
on the <i>Interceptor.</i>

1188
01:20:41,879 --> 01:20:42,963
[screeches]

1189
01:20:54,933 --> 01:20:56,977
I'm having a thought here, Barbossa.

1190
01:20:57,644 --> 01:20:59,438
What say we run up a flag of truce,

1191
01:20:59,521 --> 01:21:01,315
I scurry over to the <i>Interceptor,</i>

1192
01:21:01,398 --> 01:21:04,860
and I negotiate the return of your
medallion. What say you to that?

1193
01:21:05,819 --> 01:21:09,323
You see, Jack, that's exactly
the attitude that lost you the <i>Pearl.</i>

1194
01:21:09,406 --> 01:21:12,326
People are easier to search
when they're dead.

1195
01:21:13,369 --> 01:21:14,703
Lock him in the brig.

1196
01:21:26,965 --> 01:21:29,426
Hands aloft to loose ta'gallants!

1197
01:21:29,468 --> 01:21:32,763
With this wind dead astern,
she'll carry every sail we've got.

1198
01:21:32,805 --> 01:21:35,265
- What's happening?
- [Anamaria] The <i>Black Pearl!</i>

1199
01:21:35,307 --> 01:21:36,517
She's gaining on us!

1200
01:21:41,105 --> 01:21:43,482
This is the fastest ship
in the Caribbean!

1201
01:21:43,565 --> 01:21:46,318
You can tell them that
after they've caught us!

1202
01:21:46,360 --> 01:21:48,278
We're shallower on the draft, right?

1203
01:21:48,320 --> 01:21:49,321
Aye.

1204
01:21:49,405 --> 01:21:51,490
Can't we lose them amongst those shoals?

1205
01:21:52,950 --> 01:21:54,660
We don't have to outrun 'em long.

1206
01:21:54,701 --> 01:21:55,994
Just long enough.

1207
01:21:56,036 --> 01:21:57,329
Lighten the ship!

1208
01:21:57,413 --> 01:21:58,580
Stem to stem!

1209
01:21:58,664 --> 01:22:01,750
Anything we can afford to lose,
see that it's lost!

1210
01:22:07,047 --> 01:22:08,382
[grunts]

1211
01:22:11,176 --> 01:22:13,178
Apparently, there's a leak.

1212
01:22:26,733 --> 01:22:27,776
[squeals]

1213
01:22:27,860 --> 01:22:31,029
Haul on the main brace!
Make ready the guns!

1214
01:22:31,071 --> 01:22:33,282
And run out the sweeps.

1215
01:22:34,491 --> 01:22:35,534
[grunting]

1216
01:22:44,126 --> 01:22:45,169
[grunts]

1217
01:22:52,468 --> 01:22:53,969
[grunting]

1218
01:23:01,518 --> 01:23:03,187
We're gonna need that.

1219
01:23:09,651 --> 01:23:10,736
[exhales]

1220
01:23:11,862 --> 01:23:14,656
It was a good plan, up till now.

1221
01:23:14,740 --> 01:23:16,200
Gibbs!

1222
01:23:16,241 --> 01:23:17,659
We have to make a stand.

1223
01:23:17,743 --> 01:23:19,161
We must fight!

1224
01:23:20,078 --> 01:23:22,206
- Load the guns!
- With what?

1225
01:23:22,247 --> 01:23:23,999
Anything! Everything!

1226
01:23:24,082 --> 01:23:25,792
Anything we have left!

1227
01:23:27,836 --> 01:23:29,796
Load the guns!

1228
01:23:29,880 --> 01:23:31,590
Case shot and Iangrage!

1229
01:23:31,673 --> 01:23:33,258
Nails and crushed glass!

1230
01:23:33,300 --> 01:23:35,761
[men chattering]

1231
01:23:35,802 --> 01:23:36,970
[Gibbs] With a will!

1232
01:23:37,054 --> 01:23:39,723
[chatter continues]

1233
01:23:58,283 --> 01:24:01,119
The <i>Pearl's</i> gonna luff up
on our port quarter!

1234
01:24:01,203 --> 01:24:03,789
She'll rake us without ever
presenting a target!

1235
01:24:03,830 --> 01:24:05,916
Lower the anchor on the right side.

1236
01:24:06,500 --> 01:24:07,918
On the starboard side!

1237
01:24:08,961 --> 01:24:12,089
- It has the element of surprise.
- [Anamaria] You're daft, lady!

1238
01:24:12,130 --> 01:24:13,131
You both are!

1239
01:24:13,215 --> 01:24:14,633
Daft like Jack!

1240
01:24:15,342 --> 01:24:16,843
Lower the starboard anchor!

1241
01:24:17,469 --> 01:24:21,014
Do it, you gobs, or it's you
we'll load into the cannons!

1242
01:24:21,098 --> 01:24:22,641
[man] Aye!

1243
01:24:39,491 --> 01:24:40,742
Let go!

1244
01:24:47,332 --> 01:24:49,001
They're club haulin'!

1245
01:24:49,084 --> 01:24:51,837
Hard a port!
Rack the starboard oars!

1246
01:24:51,920 --> 01:24:53,672
Hard a port!

1247
01:25:05,058 --> 01:25:06,310
Keep her steady, man.

1248
01:25:07,936 --> 01:25:09,062
[shouting]

1249
01:25:09,146 --> 01:25:10,188
[shouting]

1250
01:25:13,358 --> 01:25:14,359
Now!

1251
01:25:14,443 --> 01:25:15,527
Fire!

1252
01:25:15,569 --> 01:25:16,737
Fire!

1253
01:25:20,782 --> 01:25:21,867
[screaming]

1254
01:25:26,496 --> 01:25:28,498
Stop blowing holes in my ship!

1255
01:26:15,087 --> 01:26:17,255
We could use a few more ideas, lass!

1256
01:26:17,339 --> 01:26:18,924
It's your turn!

1257
01:26:18,965 --> 01:26:20,759
We need us a devil's dowry!

1258
01:26:20,801 --> 01:26:22,135
We'll give them her!

1259
01:26:23,136 --> 01:26:24,638
She's not what they're after.

1260
01:26:27,224 --> 01:26:28,558
The medallion!

1261
01:26:39,986 --> 01:26:40,987
[grunts]

1262
01:26:41,071 --> 01:26:43,281
- [yelling]
- [cannon fire]

1263
01:26:43,365 --> 01:26:44,616
[grunting]

1264
01:26:49,121 --> 01:26:50,622
[screaming]

1265
01:26:50,664 --> 01:26:53,250
Strike your colours,
you bloomin' cockroaches!

1266
01:26:53,291 --> 01:26:56,044
Hands, grapnels, at the ready!

1267
01:26:56,128 --> 01:26:57,963
Prepare to board!

1268
01:27:03,885 --> 01:27:05,512
[cracking]

1269
01:27:05,595 --> 01:27:06,805
Ahh!

1270
01:27:06,888 --> 01:27:09,641
- [screaming]
- [wood creaking]

1271
01:27:24,781 --> 01:27:27,993
[groaning]

1272
01:27:28,034 --> 01:27:29,494
[shouts]

1273
01:27:32,289 --> 01:27:35,125
Pistols and cutlasses, men!

1274
01:27:35,167 --> 01:27:37,461
Koehler and Twigg
to the powder magazine!

1275
01:27:37,502 --> 01:27:40,839
And the rest of you,
bring me the medallion!

1276
01:27:50,390 --> 01:27:52,809
Hey! Hey!

1277
01:27:59,733 --> 01:28:01,526
[growling]

1278
01:28:08,617 --> 01:28:11,244
Hey! Below!

1279
01:28:11,328 --> 01:28:12,537
[screams]

1280
01:28:12,579 --> 01:28:14,289
[yells]

1281
01:28:16,625 --> 01:28:19,628
[both laughing]

1282
01:28:19,711 --> 01:28:20,921
[both grunt]

1283
01:28:22,839 --> 01:28:25,258
[gunshots whizzing]

1284
01:28:26,343 --> 01:28:27,344
[grunts]

1285
01:28:27,385 --> 01:28:29,763
[yelling]

1286
01:28:31,056 --> 01:28:32,557
Thanks very much.

1287
01:28:35,894 --> 01:28:37,479
Ha-haa!

1288
01:28:40,273 --> 01:28:41,775
[grunting]

1289
01:28:41,858 --> 01:28:44,486
Whoa!

1290
01:28:45,946 --> 01:28:46,947
Jack!

1291
01:28:48,323 --> 01:28:50,116
Bloody empty!

1292
01:28:50,575 --> 01:28:52,744
[shouting]

1293
01:28:53,745 --> 01:28:55,247
[yells]

1294
01:28:55,330 --> 01:28:57,082
[monkey screeching]

1295
01:29:06,049 --> 01:29:07,926
That's not very nice.

1296
01:29:12,556 --> 01:29:13,765
Where is the medallion?

1297
01:29:13,807 --> 01:29:14,891
Wretch!

1298
01:29:16,643 --> 01:29:17,853
Ah...

1299
01:29:17,936 --> 01:29:19,271
Where is dear William?

1300
01:29:21,481 --> 01:29:22,732
Will!

1301
01:29:24,943 --> 01:29:27,153
- Will!
- Elizabeth!

1302
01:29:30,115 --> 01:29:31,241
Monkey!

1303
01:29:37,914 --> 01:29:39,749
I can't move it!

1304
01:29:39,791 --> 01:29:41,042
[snarls]

1305
01:29:41,126 --> 01:29:42,127
Will!

1306
01:29:42,168 --> 01:29:43,295
Elizabeth!

1307
01:29:43,336 --> 01:29:44,421
Will!

1308
01:29:55,515 --> 01:29:57,642
Why, thank you, Jack.

1309
01:29:57,726 --> 01:29:59,352
You're welcome.

1310
01:29:59,436 --> 01:30:02,022
Not you. We named the monkey Jack.

1311
01:30:03,231 --> 01:30:06,151
Gents! Our hope is restored!

1312
01:30:06,234 --> 01:30:07,652
[all] Yeah!

1313
01:30:07,736 --> 01:30:10,030
[cheering shouting continue]

1314
01:30:23,627 --> 01:30:25,503
[cackling]

1315
01:30:42,187 --> 01:30:46,191
Any of you so much
as thinks the word parley,

1316
01:30:46,274 --> 01:30:49,027
I'll have your guts for garters!

1317
01:30:53,490 --> 01:30:56,868
[Barbossa laughing]

1318
01:30:56,910 --> 01:30:58,328
Will!

1319
01:30:58,370 --> 01:31:00,372
Stop it! Stop it!

1320
01:31:01,247 --> 01:31:03,208
Welcome back, miss.

1321
01:31:03,291 --> 01:31:06,044
You took advantage of
our hospitality last time.

1322
01:31:06,086 --> 01:31:09,422
It holds fair now
that you return the favour!

1323
01:31:09,839 --> 01:31:12,717
[screaming] No! No!

1324
01:31:12,759 --> 01:31:15,303
[screaming continues]

1325
01:31:15,387 --> 01:31:16,471
Barbossa!

1326
01:31:18,431 --> 01:31:19,432
Will.

1327
01:31:22,227 --> 01:31:23,228
She goes free!

1328
01:31:24,354 --> 01:31:26,064
What's in your head, boy?

1329
01:31:27,440 --> 01:31:28,733
She goes free.

1330
01:31:29,401 --> 01:31:32,445
You've only got one shot,
and we can't die.

1331
01:31:32,529 --> 01:31:34,531
Don't do anything stupid!

1332
01:31:37,492 --> 01:31:38,743
You can't.

1333
01:31:38,827 --> 01:31:40,245
I can.

1334
01:31:40,286 --> 01:31:41,913
- [gasps]
- [pirates muttering]

1335
01:31:41,955 --> 01:31:43,581
Like that.

1336
01:31:44,624 --> 01:31:45,917
Who are you?

1337
01:31:45,959 --> 01:31:47,460
No one! He's no one!

1338
01:31:48,211 --> 01:31:51,214
A distant cousin of my aunt's
nephew, twice removed.

1339
01:31:51,256 --> 01:31:53,758
Lovely singing voice, though.
[whispers] Eunuch!

1340
01:31:53,800 --> 01:31:55,468
My name is Will Turner!

1341
01:31:55,552 --> 01:31:58,263
My father was Bootstrap Bill Turner.

1342
01:31:58,304 --> 01:32:00,265
His blood runs in my veins.

1343
01:32:00,974 --> 01:32:03,268
It's the spitting image
of ol' Bootstrap Bill,

1344
01:32:03,351 --> 01:32:05,145
come back to haunt us!

1345
01:32:05,228 --> 01:32:07,230
On my word, do as I say,

1346
01:32:07,272 --> 01:32:09,149
or I'll pull this trigger,

1347
01:32:09,232 --> 01:32:11,443
and be lost to Davy Jones' locker!

1348
01:32:12,485 --> 01:32:14,779
Name your terms, Mr Turner.

1349
01:32:14,821 --> 01:32:15,989
Elizabeth goes free!

1350
01:32:16,072 --> 01:32:17,699
Yes, we know that one.

1351
01:32:17,782 --> 01:32:18,783
Anything else?

1352
01:32:21,453 --> 01:32:22,746
And the crew!

1353
01:32:22,787 --> 01:32:24,748
The crew are not to be harmed!

1354
01:32:29,502 --> 01:32:31,296
Agreed.

1355
01:32:37,510 --> 01:32:40,972
- Go on, poppet. Walk the plank.
- [Barbossa laughing]

1356
01:32:50,482 --> 01:32:52,150
Barbossa, you lying bastard!

1357
01:32:52,233 --> 01:32:54,819
You swore she'd go free!

1358
01:32:54,903 --> 01:32:57,155
Don't dare impugn me honour, boy!

1359
01:32:57,238 --> 01:32:58,907
I agreed she'd go free.

1360
01:32:58,990 --> 01:33:01,993
It was you who failed to specify
when or where.

1361
01:33:02,077 --> 01:33:04,829
- [Barbossa chuckles]
- [pirates laughing]

1362
01:33:07,707 --> 01:33:11,669
Though it does seem a shame to lose
something so fine, don't it, lads?

1363
01:33:11,711 --> 01:33:12,712
[pirates] Aye.

1364
01:33:13,713 --> 01:33:16,883
So I'll be havin' that dress
back before you go.

1365
01:33:16,966 --> 01:33:19,594
[pirates cackling]

1366
01:33:21,221 --> 01:33:23,348
- I always liked you.
- [snarls]

1367
01:33:23,431 --> 01:33:25,350
- [whistling]
- [hooting]

1368
01:33:26,351 --> 01:33:28,686
Goes with your black heart!

1369
01:33:29,270 --> 01:33:31,439
Mm. It's still warm.

1370
01:33:34,818 --> 01:33:36,861
- [Pintel] Off you go!
- [hisses]

1371
01:33:36,945 --> 01:33:38,279
Come on!

1372
01:33:40,615 --> 01:33:41,866
[chuckles]

1373
01:33:41,908 --> 01:33:43,076
Too long!

1374
01:33:43,493 --> 01:33:44,869
[shrieks]

1375
01:33:47,705 --> 01:33:50,208
[gasping panting]

1376
01:33:54,212 --> 01:33:56,714
I really rather hoped
we were past all this.

1377
01:33:58,299 --> 01:33:59,717
Jack.

1378
01:33:59,759 --> 01:34:00,844
Jack!

1379
01:34:02,595 --> 01:34:04,055
Did ya not notice?

1380
01:34:04,139 --> 01:34:08,393
That be the same island we made you
governor of on our last little trip.

1381
01:34:09,686 --> 01:34:11,354
I did notice.

1382
01:34:11,396 --> 01:34:15,567
Perhaps you'll be able to conjure up
another miraculous escape,

1383
01:34:15,608 --> 01:34:17,235
but I doubt it.

1384
01:34:20,071 --> 01:34:21,614
Off you go.

1385
01:34:22,615 --> 01:34:25,243
Last time you left me
a pistol with one shot.

1386
01:34:25,326 --> 01:34:26,911
By the powers, you're right!

1387
01:34:26,995 --> 01:34:29,122
Where be Jack's pistol?

1388
01:34:29,205 --> 01:34:30,373
Bring it forward.

1389
01:34:33,543 --> 01:34:36,337
Seeing as there's two of us,
a gentleman...

1390
01:34:37,046 --> 01:34:38,840
...would give us a pair of pistols.

1391
01:34:38,923 --> 01:34:40,633
It'll be one pistol, as before,

1392
01:34:40,717 --> 01:34:43,511
and you can be the gentleman
and shoot the lady,

1393
01:34:43,595 --> 01:34:45,430
and starve to death yourself!

1394
01:35:09,787 --> 01:35:13,333
That's the second time I've had to watch
that man sail away with my ship.

1395
01:35:15,793 --> 01:35:18,463
You were marooned on this island
before, weren't you?

1396
01:35:18,546 --> 01:35:20,131
We can escape the same way!

1397
01:35:20,173 --> 01:35:22,300
To what point and purpose, young missy?

1398
01:35:23,051 --> 01:35:24,802
The <i>Black Pearl</i> is gone,

1399
01:35:24,844 --> 01:35:28,306
and unless you have a rudder and
a lot of sails hidden in that bodice...

1400
01:35:28,389 --> 01:35:30,808
Unlikely...

1401
01:35:30,850 --> 01:35:33,811
Young Mr Turner will be dead
long before you can reach him.

1402
01:35:36,481 --> 01:35:38,816
But you're Captain Jack Sparrow!

1403
01:35:38,858 --> 01:35:43,279
You vanished from under the eyes of
seven agents of the East India Company!

1404
01:35:43,321 --> 01:35:46,074
You sacked Nassau Port
without even firing a shot!

1405
01:35:46,157 --> 01:35:48,409
Are you the pirate
I've read about or not?

1406
01:35:50,954 --> 01:35:52,455
How did you escape last time?

1407
01:35:59,295 --> 01:36:01,172
Last time...

1408
01:36:01,214 --> 01:36:04,008
...I was here a grand total
of three days, all right?

1409
01:36:05,009 --> 01:36:06,010
Last time...

1410
01:36:08,054 --> 01:36:11,349
...the rum runners used this island
as a cache.

1411
01:36:11,391 --> 01:36:13,851
They came by and I was able
to barter passage off.

1412
01:36:13,935 --> 01:36:15,687
From the looks of things,

1413
01:36:15,770 --> 01:36:17,981
they've long been out of business.

1414
01:36:18,022 --> 01:36:23,152
You probably have your bloody friend
Norrington to thank for that.

1415
01:36:23,194 --> 01:36:24,737
So that's it then?

1416
01:36:26,030 --> 01:36:29,867
That's the secret, grand adventure
of the infamous Jack Sparrow!

1417
01:36:30,868 --> 01:36:32,662
You spent three days,

1418
01:36:32,704 --> 01:36:35,039
lying on a beach, drinking rum.

1419
01:36:37,417 --> 01:36:41,212
Welcome to the Caribbean, love.

1420
01:36:49,262 --> 01:36:51,431
<i>[both] ♪ We're devils
We're black sheep</i>

1421
01:36:51,514 --> 01:36:52,682
♪ We're really bad eggs

1422
01:36:52,724 --> 01:36:55,351
<i>♪ Drink up, me hearties
Yo ho</i>

1423
01:36:55,393 --> 01:36:59,355
<i>♪ Yo ho, yo ho
A pirate's life for me</i>

1424
01:36:59,397 --> 01:37:01,232
I love this song!

1425
01:37:01,316 --> 01:37:04,193
[giggling]

1426
01:37:04,235 --> 01:37:06,404
Really bad eggs!

1427
01:37:07,822 --> 01:37:09,824
Ooh...

1428
01:37:09,907 --> 01:37:11,242
[burps]

1429
01:37:11,284 --> 01:37:13,286
When I get the <i>Pearl</i> back,

1430
01:37:13,369 --> 01:37:15,872
I'm gonna teach it to the whole crew,

1431
01:37:15,913 --> 01:37:17,457
and we'll sing it all the time!

1432
01:37:17,540 --> 01:37:21,336
And you will be positively the most
fearsome pirates in the Spanish Main!

1433
01:37:21,419 --> 01:37:23,254
Not just the Spanish Main, love.

1434
01:37:24,297 --> 01:37:26,007
The entire ocean!

1435
01:37:26,090 --> 01:37:27,842
The entire world!

1436
01:37:28,760 --> 01:37:30,762
Wherever we want to go, we go.

1437
01:37:30,803 --> 01:37:32,388
That's what a ship is, you know.

1438
01:37:32,430 --> 01:37:35,266
It's not just a keel and a hull
and a deck and sails.

1439
01:37:35,350 --> 01:37:36,851
That's what a ship needs.

1440
01:37:36,934 --> 01:37:38,936
But what a ship is...

1441
01:37:40,313 --> 01:37:43,274
What the <i>Black Pearl</i> really is...

1442
01:37:44,734 --> 01:37:47,987
...is freedom.

1443
01:37:48,988 --> 01:37:50,073
Jack...

1444
01:37:50,114 --> 01:37:54,869
It must be really terrible for you
to be trapped on this island.

1445
01:37:55,661 --> 01:37:56,871
Oh, yes.

1446
01:37:56,954 --> 01:37:59,791
But the company is...

1447
01:37:59,832 --> 01:38:02,627
...infinitely better than last time,
and the...

1448
01:38:04,420 --> 01:38:08,132
- ...scenery has definitely improved.
- Mr Sparrow!

1449
01:38:08,174 --> 01:38:12,220
I'm not entirely sure I've had
enough rum to allow that kind of talk.

1450
01:38:13,846 --> 01:38:15,640
I know exactly what you mean, love.

1451
01:38:23,147 --> 01:38:24,690
To freedom!

1452
01:38:27,443 --> 01:38:28,986
To the <i>Black Pearl.</i>

1453
01:38:33,866 --> 01:38:39,414
[gulping]

1454
01:38:39,497 --> 01:38:40,498
[thud]

1455
01:38:42,083 --> 01:38:45,503
[muttering]

1456
01:38:45,586 --> 01:38:47,046
Hm?

1457
01:38:47,130 --> 01:38:48,631
Hm?

1458
01:38:58,516 --> 01:38:59,600
No!

1459
01:38:59,684 --> 01:39:02,478
Not good! Stop!

1460
01:39:02,520 --> 01:39:03,729
Not good!

1461
01:39:03,813 --> 01:39:04,814
What are you doing?

1462
01:39:04,856 --> 01:39:06,941
You've burned all the food, the shade...

1463
01:39:07,024 --> 01:39:09,277
- ...the rum!
- Yes, the rum is gone.

1464
01:39:09,360 --> 01:39:10,611
Why is the rum gone?

1465
01:39:11,070 --> 01:39:12,947
One, because it is a vile drink

1466
01:39:13,030 --> 01:39:15,950
that turns even the most respectable
men into scoundrels.

1467
01:39:16,033 --> 01:39:19,120
Two, that signal
is over 1.000 feet high.

1468
01:39:19,203 --> 01:39:21,414
The entire Royal Navy
is out looking for me.

1469
01:39:21,497 --> 01:39:23,875
Do you think there is even
the slightest chance

1470
01:39:23,916 --> 01:39:25,084
they won't see it?

1471
01:39:25,168 --> 01:39:27,003
But why is the rum gone?

1472
01:39:28,087 --> 01:39:29,547
Just wait, Captain Sparrow.

1473
01:39:29,589 --> 01:39:31,382
You give it one hour, maybe two,

1474
01:39:31,466 --> 01:39:36,387
keep a weather eye open, and you
will see white sails on that horizon.

1475
01:39:41,893 --> 01:39:44,896
"Must've been terrible for you
to be trapped here, Jack."

1476
01:39:44,937 --> 01:39:48,024
"Must've been terrible for you..."
Well, it bloody is now!

1477
01:39:55,406 --> 01:39:57,658
There'll be no
living with her after this.

1478
01:39:58,659 --> 01:40:00,735
- [Elizabeth] We've got to save Will!
- No! You're safe now.

1479
01:40:00,745 --> 01:40:02,246
- [Elizabeth] We've got to save Will!
- No! You're safe now.

1480
01:40:02,330 --> 01:40:04,415
We will return to
Port Royal immediately,

1481
01:40:04,499 --> 01:40:06,459
not go gallivanting after pirates!

1482
01:40:06,542 --> 01:40:08,461
Then we condemn him to death!

1483
01:40:09,545 --> 01:40:12,256
The boy's fate is regrettable...

1484
01:40:12,340 --> 01:40:14,926
...but then, so was his decision
to engage in piracy.

1485
01:40:15,009 --> 01:40:18,262
To rescue me! To prevent anything
from happening to me!

1486
01:40:18,346 --> 01:40:22,183
If I may be so bold as to interject
my professional opinion,

1487
01:40:22,266 --> 01:40:25,436
the <i>Pearl</i> was listing
near to scuppers after the battle.

1488
01:40:25,478 --> 01:40:28,397
It's very unlikely she'd be able
to make good time.

1489
01:40:28,439 --> 01:40:29,774
Think about it.

1490
01:40:29,857 --> 01:40:32,068
The <i>Black Pearl.</i>

1491
01:40:32,109 --> 01:40:36,614
The last real pirate threat
in the Caribbean, mate.

1492
01:40:36,656 --> 01:40:38,616
How can you pass that up?

1493
01:40:40,785 --> 01:40:43,621
By remembering that I serve others,
Mr Sparrow,

1494
01:40:43,663 --> 01:40:46,165
- not only myself.
- Commodore, I beg you!

1495
01:40:46,249 --> 01:40:47,250
Please do this!

1496
01:40:47,291 --> 01:40:48,918
For me!

1497
01:40:48,960 --> 01:40:51,128
As a wedding gift.

1498
01:40:51,212 --> 01:40:52,380
Elizabeth?

1499
01:40:53,464 --> 01:40:56,008
Are you accepting
the commodore's proposal?

1500
01:40:58,427 --> 01:40:59,470
lam.

1501
01:41:00,304 --> 01:41:01,973
A wedding! I love weddings!

1502
01:41:02,056 --> 01:41:03,808
Drinks all around!

1503
01:41:06,102 --> 01:41:08,854
I know. "Clap him in irons," right?

1504
01:41:11,399 --> 01:41:12,567
Mr Sparrow...

1505
01:41:13,901 --> 01:41:16,237
...you will accompany
these fine men to the helm

1506
01:41:16,320 --> 01:41:18,823
and provide us with a bearing
to Isla de Muerta.

1507
01:41:18,864 --> 01:41:22,785
You'll then spend the rest of the voyage
contemplating all possible meanings

1508
01:41:22,827 --> 01:41:25,329
of the phrase "silent as the grave."

1509
01:41:25,371 --> 01:41:26,956
Do I make myself clear?

1510
01:41:26,998 --> 01:41:29,083
Inescapably clear.

1511
01:41:33,087 --> 01:41:35,339
[squawks] Shiver me timbers!

1512
01:41:36,132 --> 01:41:37,758
Cotton says you missed a bit.

1513
01:41:39,343 --> 01:41:40,845
[Ragetti giggles]

1514
01:41:42,763 --> 01:41:44,140
You knew William Turner?

1515
01:41:46,017 --> 01:41:48,102
Old Bootstrap Bill.

1516
01:41:48,185 --> 01:41:49,186
We knew him.

1517
01:41:50,187 --> 01:41:54,191
Never sat well with Bootstrap,
what we did to Jack Sparrow,

1518
01:41:54,233 --> 01:41:56,319
the mutiny and all.

1519
01:41:56,902 --> 01:41:58,904
He said it wasn't right with the code.

1520
01:41:59,989 --> 01:42:03,159
That's why he sent off a piece
of the treasure to you, as it were.

1521
01:42:03,200 --> 01:42:06,829
He said we deserved to be cursed...

1522
01:42:08,414 --> 01:42:10,499
...and remain cursed.

1523
01:42:10,541 --> 01:42:11,584
Stupid blighter!

1524
01:42:11,667 --> 01:42:13,502
Good man.

1525
01:42:13,544 --> 01:42:18,799
But, as you can imagine, that
didn't sit too well with the captain.

1526
01:42:18,883 --> 01:42:22,136
That didn't sit too well
with the captain at all!

1527
01:42:22,219 --> 01:42:25,848
- Tell him what Barbossa did.
- I'm telling the story!

1528
01:42:28,392 --> 01:42:32,480
So... what the captain did...

1529
01:42:32,563 --> 01:42:35,149
...he strapped a cannon
to Bootstrap's bootstraps.

1530
01:42:35,232 --> 01:42:36,734
Bootstrap's bootstraps.

1531
01:42:36,776 --> 01:42:39,779
Last we saw of ol' Bill Turner...

1532
01:42:39,862 --> 01:42:42,323
...he was sinking to
the crushin' black oblivion

1533
01:42:42,406 --> 01:42:45,534
of Davy Jones' locker!

1534
01:42:45,951 --> 01:42:49,038
'Course it was only after that
we learned we needed his blood

1535
01:42:49,080 --> 01:42:50,289
to lift the curse.

1536
01:42:50,373 --> 01:42:53,417
That's what you'd call ironic.

1537
01:42:54,085 --> 01:42:56,671
- [both giggle]
- [footsteps approaching]

1538
01:42:57,588 --> 01:42:59,215
Bring him!

1539
01:43:06,430 --> 01:43:08,432
I don't care for the situation.

1540
01:43:08,974 --> 01:43:12,061
Any attempt to storm the caves
could turn into an ambush.

1541
01:43:12,103 --> 01:43:15,439
Not if you're the one
doing the ambushing.

1542
01:43:15,523 --> 01:43:19,193
I go in and convince Barbossa to send
his men out in their little boats.

1543
01:43:19,276 --> 01:43:22,113
You and your men
return to the <i>Dauntless</i>

1544
01:43:22,154 --> 01:43:25,408
and blast the bejesus out of them
with your little cannons.

1545
01:43:25,449 --> 01:43:26,701
What do you have to lose?

1546
01:43:27,785 --> 01:43:30,287
Nothing I'd lament being rid of.

1547
01:43:31,956 --> 01:43:33,833
Now, to be quite honest with you,

1548
01:43:33,916 --> 01:43:36,877
there's still a slight risk
to those aboard the <i>Dauntless,</i>

1549
01:43:36,961 --> 01:43:40,756
which includes
the future Mrs Commodore.

1550
01:43:40,798 --> 01:43:43,884
- It's for your safety!
- Don't care what the Commodore ordered!

1551
01:43:43,968 --> 01:43:44,969
I have to tell him!

1552
01:43:45,010 --> 01:43:48,013
The pirates! They're cursed!
They can't be killed!

1553
01:43:48,097 --> 01:43:50,641
Don't worry, miss.
He's already informed of that.

1554
01:43:50,683 --> 01:43:54,395
A little mermaid flopped up on deck
and told him the whole story!

1555
01:43:54,478 --> 01:43:56,564
This is Jack Sparrow's doing!

1556
01:43:57,064 --> 01:43:58,983
[sighs]

1557
01:44:08,033 --> 01:44:09,493
No reason to fret.

1558
01:44:09,577 --> 01:44:12,163
Just a prick of the finger,
a few drops of blood...

1559
01:44:12,204 --> 01:44:14,206
No mistakes this time.

1560
01:44:14,290 --> 01:44:16,000
He's only half Turner.

1561
01:44:16,083 --> 01:44:17,501
We spill it all!

1562
01:44:18,252 --> 01:44:19,837
[grunts]

1563
01:44:19,920 --> 01:44:22,840
- Guess there is reason to fret.
- [snorts]

1564
01:44:22,882 --> 01:44:26,051
[pirates chanting]

1565
01:44:35,686 --> 01:44:37,563
Beg your pardon, mate.
Beg your pardon.

1566
01:44:37,646 --> 01:44:39,690
- [Barbossa] Begun by blood...
- Excuse me.

1567
01:44:39,774 --> 01:44:42,485
By blood un...

1568
01:44:44,862 --> 01:44:45,863
Jack!

1569
01:44:46,906 --> 01:44:47,990
It's not possible!

1570
01:44:48,032 --> 01:44:50,201
Not probable.

1571
01:44:50,242 --> 01:44:52,036
Where's Elizabeth?

1572
01:44:53,412 --> 01:44:55,664
She's safe, just like I promised.

1573
01:44:55,706 --> 01:44:58,667
She's all set to marry Norrington,
just like she promised,

1574
01:44:58,709 --> 01:45:01,086
and you get to die for her,
just like you promised.

1575
01:45:01,170 --> 01:45:03,297
So we're all men of our word, really.

1576
01:45:03,380 --> 01:45:06,675
Except for Elizabeth,
who is, in fact, a woman.

1577
01:45:06,717 --> 01:45:08,135
Shut up! You're next!

1578
01:45:11,680 --> 01:45:14,558
You don't want to be doing that, mate.

1579
01:45:14,600 --> 01:45:16,560
No, I really think I do.

1580
01:45:18,354 --> 01:45:20,231
Your funeral.

1581
01:45:23,400 --> 01:45:25,402
And why don't I want to be doing it?

1582
01:45:25,444 --> 01:45:27,112
Oh, because...

1583
01:45:28,113 --> 01:45:30,449
Because the <i>HMS Dauntless,</i>

1584
01:45:30,533 --> 01:45:32,952
the pride of the Royal Navy,

1585
01:45:33,035 --> 01:45:36,288
is floating just off shore,

1586
01:45:36,372 --> 01:45:38,207
waiting for you.

1587
01:45:38,249 --> 01:45:40,459
[murmuring]

1588
01:45:46,257 --> 01:45:47,424
What we doing here?

1589
01:45:49,343 --> 01:45:52,763
The pirates come out,
unprepared and unawares.

1590
01:45:52,805 --> 01:45:54,890
We catch 'em in a crossfire,

1591
01:45:54,932 --> 01:45:57,768
and send 'em down to see Old Hob.

1592
01:45:59,061 --> 01:46:01,438
I know why we're here. I meant...

1593
01:46:01,522 --> 01:46:03,399
.__why aren't we doing what it was...

1594
01:46:03,440 --> 01:46:05,276
What Mr Sparrow said we should do?

1595
01:46:05,317 --> 01:46:06,819
With the cannons and all?

1596
01:46:06,902 --> 01:46:09,947
Because it was Mr Sparrow who said it.

1597
01:46:12,575 --> 01:46:15,160
You think he wasn't telling the truth?

1598
01:46:15,244 --> 01:46:17,121
Just hear me out, mate.

1599
01:46:17,204 --> 01:46:20,958
You order your men to row out to the
<i>Dauntless,</i> they do what they do best...

1600
01:46:22,042 --> 01:46:26,463
Robert's your uncle, Fanny's your aunt.
There you are with two ships.

1601
01:46:26,547 --> 01:46:28,966
The makings of your very own fleet.

1602
01:46:29,049 --> 01:46:32,636
'Course, you'll take the grandest
as your flagship, and who's to argue?

1603
01:46:32,720 --> 01:46:34,138
But what of the <i>Pearl?</i>

1604
01:46:35,764 --> 01:46:37,099
Name me captain.

1605
01:46:37,141 --> 01:46:40,603
I'II sail under your colours,
I'll give you ten percent of me plunder,

1606
01:46:40,644 --> 01:46:42,855
and you'll get to
introduce yourself as...

1607
01:46:43,439 --> 01:46:46,317
...Commodore Barbossa.

1608
01:46:46,358 --> 01:46:47,443
Savvy?

1609
01:46:47,484 --> 01:46:49,695
I suppose, in exchange, you'll be

1610
01:46:49,778 --> 01:46:52,615
- wanting me not to kill the whelp.
- No. Not at all!

1611
01:46:52,656 --> 01:46:54,325
By all means, kill the whelp!

1612
01:46:54,366 --> 01:46:56,785
Just not yet.

1613
01:46:56,827 --> 01:46:58,996
Wait to lift the curse

1614
01:46:59,038 --> 01:47:01,707
until the opportune moment.

1615
01:47:05,169 --> 01:47:06,795
For instance...

1616
01:47:08,672 --> 01:47:11,926
...after you've killed Norrington's men.

1617
01:47:12,009 --> 01:47:13,594
Every...

1618
01:47:13,677 --> 01:47:15,346
…last…

1619
01:47:15,387 --> 01:47:16,847
..one.

1620
01:47:26,482 --> 01:47:28,817
You've been planning this
from the beginning!

1621
01:47:28,859 --> 01:47:30,444
Ever since you learned my name!

1622
01:47:31,278 --> 01:47:32,279
Yeah.

1623
01:47:34,615 --> 01:47:36,742
I want 50 percent of your plunder.

1624
01:47:36,825 --> 01:47:37,826
-15!
-40!

1625
01:47:37,868 --> 01:47:38,869
25!

1626
01:47:40,037 --> 01:47:41,372
And I'll buy you the hat.

1627
01:47:41,413 --> 01:47:43,415
A really big one.

1628
01:47:44,208 --> 01:47:45,376
Commodore.

1629
01:47:48,504 --> 01:47:49,713
We have an accord.

1630
01:47:51,382 --> 01:47:53,676
All hands to the boats!

1631
01:47:54,677 --> 01:47:55,803
Apologies.

1632
01:47:55,886 --> 01:47:57,554
You give the orders.

1633
01:47:58,889 --> 01:47:59,890
Gents...

1634
01:48:00,891 --> 01:48:02,267
...take a walk!

1635
01:48:02,351 --> 01:48:06,063
[chattering]

1636
01:48:07,106 --> 01:48:08,440
Not to the boats?

1637
01:49:07,833 --> 01:49:10,753
Hold fire!

1638
01:49:12,796 --> 01:49:15,591
This is just like what
the Greeks done at Troy!

1639
01:49:16,967 --> 01:49:18,594
'Cept they was in a horse,

1640
01:49:18,635 --> 01:49:20,095
instead of dresses.

1641
01:49:20,804 --> 01:49:22,181
Wooden horse.

1642
01:49:35,152 --> 01:49:36,153
A moment, please.

1643
01:49:40,324 --> 01:49:41,325
Elizabeth?

1644
01:49:44,578 --> 01:49:46,371
I just want you to know, I...

1645
01:49:47,498 --> 01:49:49,958
I believe you made a very
good decision today.

1646
01:49:50,793 --> 01:49:52,795
Couldn't be more proud of you!

1647
01:49:53,295 --> 01:49:54,421
But, you know,

1648
01:49:54,505 --> 01:49:57,424
even a good decision,
if made for the wrong reasons,

1649
01:49:57,508 --> 01:49:59,009
can be a wrong decision.

1650
01:50:08,018 --> 01:50:09,019
Lieutenant.

1651
01:50:15,943 --> 01:50:18,362
Yoo-hoo.

1652
01:50:28,205 --> 01:50:29,373
Elizabeth?

1653
01:50:31,542 --> 01:50:32,793
Are you there?

1654
01:50:35,045 --> 01:50:37,673
Elizabeth, are you even listening to me?

1655
01:50:51,562 --> 01:50:54,398
- [cracking]
- [groan]

1656
01:51:04,116 --> 01:51:06,869
Oh, what have you done?

1657
01:51:06,910 --> 01:51:10,497
- Yoo-hoo.
- Stop that! I already feel like a fool!

1658
01:51:11,540 --> 01:51:14,042
- Look nice, though.
- [sighs]

1659
01:51:14,084 --> 01:51:15,419
[growls]

1660
01:51:15,502 --> 01:51:17,379
[grunts]

1661
01:51:17,421 --> 01:51:19,840
Do I look nice now?!

1662
01:51:21,133 --> 01:51:23,260
[choking grunting]

1663
01:51:26,054 --> 01:51:28,599
[all shout]

1664
01:51:36,273 --> 01:51:38,984
[groaning]

1665
01:51:40,777 --> 01:51:41,904
[gasps]

1666
01:51:43,614 --> 01:51:44,698
[snarls]

1667
01:51:48,952 --> 01:51:53,457
[water plopping]

1668
01:51:55,792 --> 01:51:57,044
I must admit, Jack.

1669
01:51:57,127 --> 01:51:59,046
I thought I had you figured.

1670
01:51:59,129 --> 01:52:02,299
But it turns out you're
a hard man to predict.

1671
01:52:02,382 --> 01:52:04,343
Me, I'm dishonest.

1672
01:52:04,426 --> 01:52:07,262
And a dishonest man you can
always trust to be dishonest.

1673
01:52:07,304 --> 01:52:08,555
Honestly...

1674
01:52:08,639 --> 01:52:11,266
...it's the honest ones
you want to watch out for.

1675
01:52:11,308 --> 01:52:13,602
'Cause you can never predict

1676
01:52:13,644 --> 01:52:16,939
when they're going to do
something incredibly...

1677
01:52:16,980 --> 01:52:17,981
…stupid.

1678
01:52:19,441 --> 01:52:20,567
[yells]

1679
01:52:35,624 --> 01:52:36,792
Ha-ha!

1680
01:52:36,833 --> 01:52:37,876
[Barbossa] Ha-ha!

1681
01:52:37,960 --> 01:52:39,294
Ha!

1682
01:52:43,465 --> 01:52:45,217
[grunts, growls]

1683
01:52:45,300 --> 01:52:46,885
[grunts, yelps]

1684
01:52:51,139 --> 01:52:53,350
You're off the edge of the map, mate.

1685
01:52:53,433 --> 01:52:55,477
Here, there be monsters!

1686
01:53:00,357 --> 01:53:03,318
[pirate] Right. [cackling]

1687
01:53:03,360 --> 01:53:05,445
What would you pick to eat first?

1688
01:53:05,529 --> 01:53:07,447
I think we should decide now,

1689
01:53:07,531 --> 01:53:09,700
just so we're ready when the time comes!

1690
01:53:12,411 --> 01:53:16,206
[Elizabeth panting]

1691
01:53:26,425 --> 01:53:28,719
- [gasps]
- [screeches]

1692
01:53:34,766 --> 01:53:35,892
What was that?

1693
01:53:40,397 --> 01:53:41,440
Oh.

1694
01:53:47,487 --> 01:53:50,741
[yelling]

1695
01:53:54,119 --> 01:53:56,371
- [murmuring]
- Shh!

1696
01:53:58,832 --> 01:53:59,833
It's Elizabeth!

1697
01:53:59,916 --> 01:54:02,210
[grunting]

1698
01:54:02,252 --> 01:54:03,253
[groans]

1699
01:54:17,601 --> 01:54:20,395
- [bell tolling]
- [shots firing]

1700
01:54:20,437 --> 01:54:22,105
Make for the ship! Move!

1701
01:54:26,276 --> 01:54:27,694
Ahh!

1702
01:54:31,531 --> 01:54:33,325
[Norrington] To the ship!

1703
01:54:36,119 --> 01:54:39,247
Marines, arms!

1704
01:54:43,627 --> 01:54:45,629
[stifled gasps]

1705
01:54:45,670 --> 01:54:47,798
- [gunshot]
- [groaning]

1706
01:54:51,843 --> 01:54:52,969
[gasps]

1707
01:54:53,387 --> 01:54:56,264
[screaming]

1708
01:54:58,266 --> 01:55:00,143
[grunting straining]

1709
01:55:12,114 --> 01:55:13,407
[grunts]

1710
01:55:15,700 --> 01:55:17,452
You can't beat me, Jack.

1711
01:55:22,457 --> 01:55:23,708
[sighs]

1712
01:55:25,168 --> 01:55:26,169
[grunts]

1713
01:55:26,211 --> 01:55:28,380
[gasps, gurgles]

1714
01:55:41,726 --> 01:55:43,270
That's interesting!

1715
01:55:46,606 --> 01:55:48,024
[splash]

1716
01:55:54,156 --> 01:55:56,032
I couldn't resist, mate.

1717
01:55:56,116 --> 01:55:57,617
[scoffs]

1718
01:55:59,870 --> 01:56:01,705
[shouts]

1719
01:56:02,539 --> 01:56:05,041
[both grunting]

1720
01:56:18,096 --> 01:56:20,348
Oh, no.

1721
01:56:31,109 --> 01:56:33,361
[whimpering]

1722
01:56:59,054 --> 01:57:00,305
[grunting]

1723
01:57:00,388 --> 01:57:02,390
[groans]

1724
01:57:02,432 --> 01:57:03,642
Sorry!

1725
01:57:10,148 --> 01:57:12,651
[grunts, panting]

1726
01:57:12,734 --> 01:57:14,402
So, what now, Jack Sparrow?

1727
01:57:14,444 --> 01:57:17,113
Are we to be two immortals,
locked in an epic battle

1728
01:57:17,197 --> 01:57:19,533
until Judgment Day,
when the trumpets sound?

1729
01:57:19,616 --> 01:57:20,617
Hm?

1730
01:57:20,659 --> 01:57:22,077
Or you could surrender.

1731
01:57:29,125 --> 01:57:30,585
[grunts]

1732
01:57:30,835 --> 01:57:34,172
Ahh!

1733
01:57:34,256 --> 01:57:35,121
Ah-ha-ha-ha-ha.

1734
01:57:35,131 --> 01:57:36,091
Ah-ha-ha-ha-ha.

1735
01:57:47,686 --> 01:57:49,312
[cheering]

1736
01:57:49,396 --> 01:57:50,605
All of you with me!

1737
01:57:50,647 --> 01:57:52,732
Will is in that cave,
and we must save him!

1738
01:57:52,816 --> 01:57:55,402
Ready, and... heave!

1739
01:57:56,152 --> 01:58:00,824
[creaking]

1740
01:58:01,992 --> 01:58:03,994
Please, I need your help! Come on!

1741
01:58:04,077 --> 01:58:06,830
[squawks] Any port in a storm.

1742
01:58:06,913 --> 01:58:08,999
Cotton's right. We've got the <i>Pearl!</i>

1743
01:58:09,082 --> 01:58:11,334
What about Jack?
Are you just gonna leave him?

1744
01:58:11,418 --> 01:58:13,211
Jack owes us a ship!

1745
01:58:13,295 --> 01:58:14,838
There's the code to consider.

1746
01:58:15,422 --> 01:58:16,548
The code?

1747
01:58:18,300 --> 01:58:20,760
You're pirates!
Hang the code

1748
01:58:20,844 --> 01:58:22,512
and hang the rules!

1749
01:58:22,554 --> 01:58:24,973
They're more like guidelines, anyway.

1750
01:58:28,768 --> 01:58:30,937
Bloody pirates!

1751
01:58:34,858 --> 01:58:36,192
[groans]

1752
01:58:40,530 --> 01:58:42,282
- Oi!
- What?

1753
01:58:42,365 --> 01:58:44,534
Is it supposed to be doing that?

1754
01:58:44,618 --> 01:58:46,828
They're stealing our ship!

1755
01:58:47,287 --> 01:58:48,955
Bloody pirates!

1756
01:58:51,041 --> 01:58:52,876
Boarders away!

1757
01:59:01,092 --> 01:59:03,094
Come on!

1758
01:59:03,178 --> 01:59:04,929
[yells]

1759
01:59:08,266 --> 01:59:09,601
[grunts]

1760
01:59:21,071 --> 01:59:22,405
[whimpering]

1761
01:59:22,447 --> 01:59:23,948
[grunts, giggles]

1762
01:59:28,286 --> 01:59:30,330
No! Me eye!

1763
01:59:31,414 --> 01:59:33,124
No! [whimpers]

1764
01:59:40,799 --> 01:59:42,425
[both shout]

1765
01:59:42,509 --> 01:59:44,302
[shouts, laughs]

1766
01:59:47,430 --> 01:59:48,973
Ha!

1767
01:59:50,266 --> 01:59:52,352
I'm gonna teach you the meaning of pain!

1768
01:59:52,435 --> 01:59:53,978
You like pain?

1769
01:59:54,062 --> 01:59:55,772
[groans]

1770
01:59:55,814 --> 01:59:57,190
Try wearing a corset.

1771
02:00:00,360 --> 02:00:03,154
[panting]

1772
02:00:05,031 --> 02:00:06,408
[groans]

1773
02:00:07,575 --> 02:00:09,202
Whose side is Jack on?

1774
02:00:09,285 --> 02:00:12,330
At the moment?

1775
02:00:13,331 --> 02:00:14,791
- [chuckles]
- [grunts]

1776
02:00:25,802 --> 02:00:27,804
[screaming]

1777
02:00:45,238 --> 02:00:46,489
[whimpering]

1778
02:00:46,531 --> 02:00:48,408
[gasps] No fair!

1779
02:01:04,132 --> 02:01:06,384
- [gunshot]
- [gasps]

1780
02:01:12,432 --> 02:01:14,267
Ten years you carry that pistol,

1781
02:01:14,350 --> 02:01:16,686
and now you waste your shot!

1782
02:01:17,687 --> 02:01:20,648
He didn't waste it.

1783
02:01:25,862 --> 02:01:27,906
[gasps]

1784
02:01:30,200 --> 02:01:31,701
[sword clatters]

1785
02:01:39,626 --> 02:01:41,377
[scoffs]

1786
02:01:45,298 --> 02:01:46,800
I feel...

1787
02:01:51,387 --> 02:01:52,680
…cold.

1788
02:02:02,190 --> 02:02:04,943
- [yelling]
- [groans]

1789
02:02:05,026 --> 02:02:08,571
[pirates murmuring]

1790
02:02:12,075 --> 02:02:13,618
[groans]

1791
02:02:22,794 --> 02:02:25,797
Oh... Ugh! Oh!

1792
02:02:47,944 --> 02:02:49,112
[blows]

1793
02:02:54,951 --> 02:02:57,412
Parley?

1794
02:02:57,453 --> 02:02:59,330
The ship is ours, gentlemen.

1795
02:02:59,414 --> 02:03:01,791
[all] Huzzah! Huzzah!

1796
02:03:01,875 --> 02:03:06,254
[chanting continues]

1797
02:03:10,592 --> 02:03:11,968
Huzzah!

1798
02:03:12,051 --> 02:03:13,469
Huzzah!

1799
02:03:37,827 --> 02:03:39,329
[clattering]

1800
02:03:47,670 --> 02:03:50,006
We should return to the <i>Dauntless.</i>

1801
02:03:52,550 --> 02:03:56,179
Your fiancé will be wanting
to know you're safe.

1802
02:04:00,892 --> 02:04:03,561
[footsteps retreating]

1803
02:04:05,855 --> 02:04:09,150
If you were waiting for
the opportune moment...

1804
02:04:10,151 --> 02:04:11,486
…that was it.

1805
02:04:12,946 --> 02:04:15,114
Now if you'd be so kind,
I'd be much obliged

1806
02:04:15,198 --> 02:04:18,034
if you'd drop me off at my ship.

1807
02:04:22,622 --> 02:04:24,791
I'm sorry, Jack.

1808
02:04:26,709 --> 02:04:28,920
They done what's right by them.

1809
02:04:29,003 --> 02:04:30,755
Can't expect more than that.

1810
02:04:31,798 --> 02:04:34,884
[drumming]

1811
02:04:46,354 --> 02:04:47,689
Jack Sparrow!

1812
02:04:47,730 --> 02:04:51,818
- We have learned that you...
- Captain! Captain Jack Sparrow.

1813
02:04:52,527 --> 02:04:55,780
...for your wilful commission
of crimes against the crown.

1814
02:04:55,863 --> 02:04:59,575
Said crimes being numerous in quantity,

1815
02:04:59,659 --> 02:05:01,202
and sinister in nature.

1816
02:05:01,869 --> 02:05:03,371
The most egregious of these

1817
02:05:03,413 --> 02:05:05,623
to be cited herewith:

1818
02:05:05,707 --> 02:05:09,460
- Piracy, smuggling...
- This is wrong.

1819
02:05:10,461 --> 02:05:13,464
Commodore Norrington
is bound by the law,

1820
02:05:13,548 --> 02:05:16,092
as are we all.

1821
02:05:16,134 --> 02:05:18,845
...impersonating an officer
of the Spanish Royal Navy,

1822
02:05:18,928 --> 02:05:22,015
impersonating a cleric
of the Church of England...

1823
02:05:22,098 --> 02:05:23,224
Oh, yes!

1824
02:05:23,266 --> 02:05:25,268
Sailing under false colours,

1825
02:05:25,351 --> 02:05:29,564
- arson, kidnapping, looting, poaching,
- [squawks]

1826
02:05:29,605 --> 02:05:35,570
brigandage, pilfering,
depravity, depredation,

1827
02:05:35,611 --> 02:05:37,405
and general lawlessness.

1828
02:05:37,447 --> 02:05:38,781
[parrot squawking]

1829
02:05:38,823 --> 02:05:40,491
And for these crimes,

1830
02:05:40,575 --> 02:05:43,119
you have been sentenced to be,
on this day,

1831
02:05:43,161 --> 02:05:46,914
hung by the neck, until dead.

1832
02:05:46,956 --> 02:05:49,250
May God have mercy on your soul.

1833
02:05:49,292 --> 02:05:50,835
Governor Swann.

1834
02:05:50,918 --> 02:05:52,837
Commodore.

1835
02:05:54,338 --> 02:05:55,339
Elizabeth.

1836
02:05:56,799 --> 02:05:59,635
I should've told you every day,
from the moment I met you.

1837
02:06:02,430 --> 02:06:03,973
I love you.

1838
02:06:18,529 --> 02:06:20,281
[woman] Oi, watch yourself!

1839
02:06:20,323 --> 02:06:21,449
Marines!

1840
02:06:21,491 --> 02:06:23,034
I can't breathe!

1841
02:06:24,827 --> 02:06:25,870
Elizabeth!

1842
02:06:25,953 --> 02:06:28,164
[crowd screaming]

1843
02:06:28,956 --> 02:06:29,999
Move!

1844
02:06:30,875 --> 02:06:33,169
- Goodness sake!
- [gasps]

1845
02:06:40,885 --> 02:06:43,096
[officer] You men! With me!

1846
02:06:45,473 --> 02:06:47,058
[people screaming]

1847
02:06:47,141 --> 02:06:48,684
[grunting]

1848
02:06:54,357 --> 02:06:55,525
Move!

1849
02:07:05,284 --> 02:07:06,869
Come on!

1850
02:07:06,911 --> 02:07:08,746
- [yells]
- [grunts]

1851
02:07:16,963 --> 02:07:18,089
Come on, men!

1852
02:07:29,225 --> 02:07:30,226
[groans]

1853
02:07:43,698 --> 02:07:47,702
I thought we might have to endure some
manner of ill-conceived escape attempt.

1854
02:07:48,536 --> 02:07:50,121
But not from you.

1855
02:07:50,204 --> 02:07:54,041
On our return to Port Royal,
I granted you clemency.

1856
02:07:54,083 --> 02:07:55,751
And this is how you thank me?

1857
02:07:55,793 --> 02:07:57,879
By throwing in your lot with him?

1858
02:07:57,920 --> 02:07:59,505
He's a pirate!

1859
02:07:59,589 --> 02:08:01,549
- And a good man.
- [sword clatters]

1860
02:08:02,341 --> 02:08:04,594
If all I've achieved here
is that the hangman

1861
02:08:04,635 --> 02:08:06,762
will own two pairs
of boots instead of one,

1862
02:08:06,846 --> 02:08:08,472
so be it.

1863
02:08:08,556 --> 02:08:10,433
At least my conscience will be clear.

1864
02:08:10,474 --> 02:08:13,436
You forget your place, Turner.

1865
02:08:14,979 --> 02:08:16,606
It's right here,

1866
02:08:16,647 --> 02:08:18,107
between you and Jack.

1867
02:08:22,111 --> 02:08:23,779
As is mine.

1868
02:08:23,863 --> 02:08:25,239
[Swann] Elizabeth!

1869
02:08:26,699 --> 02:08:27,867
Lower your weapons.

1870
02:08:28,659 --> 02:08:30,661
For goodness sake, put them down!

1871
02:08:35,750 --> 02:08:38,669
So this is where
your heart truly lies, then.

1872
02:08:40,296 --> 02:08:41,797
It is.

1873
02:08:50,306 --> 02:08:53,935
Well! I'm actually feeling
rather good about this.

1874
02:08:53,976 --> 02:08:56,520
I think we've all arrived
at a very special place, eh?

1875
02:08:56,604 --> 02:08:57,897
- Oh.
- Spiritually.

1876
02:08:57,980 --> 02:08:59,982
Ecumenically.

1877
02:09:00,066 --> 02:09:02,151
- Grammatically.
- [scoffs]

1878
02:09:02,735 --> 02:09:05,321
I want you to know that
I was rooting for you, mate.

1879
02:09:06,614 --> 02:09:07,615
Know that.

1880
02:09:11,619 --> 02:09:13,120
Elizabeth.

1881
02:09:15,081 --> 02:09:17,667
It would never have worked
between us, darling.

1882
02:09:19,126 --> 02:09:21,003
I'm sorry.

1883
02:09:23,130 --> 02:09:24,131
Will!

1884
02:09:26,425 --> 02:09:28,094
Nice hat.

1885
02:09:30,054 --> 02:09:31,639
Friends!

1886
02:09:33,557 --> 02:09:36,352
This the day that you will always

1887
02:09:36,394 --> 02:09:39,021
remember as the day that...

1888
02:09:43,985 --> 02:09:46,654
Idiot! He's nowhere to go
but back to the noose!

1889
02:09:46,696 --> 02:09:49,031
[gasps, panting]

1890
02:09:49,073 --> 02:09:50,908
[man] Sail ho!

1891
02:09:58,457 --> 02:10:01,085
What's your plan of action?

1892
02:10:01,836 --> 02:10:02,837
Sir?

1893
02:10:07,216 --> 02:10:09,677
Perhaps on the rare occasion

1894
02:10:09,719 --> 02:10:13,597
pursuing the right course
demands an act of piracy,

1895
02:10:13,681 --> 02:10:17,476
piracy itself can be the right course?

1896
02:10:21,731 --> 02:10:23,024
Mr Turner!

1897
02:10:29,113 --> 02:10:31,949
I will accept the consequences
of my actions.

1898
02:10:37,913 --> 02:10:39,540
This is a beautiful sword.

1899
02:10:42,001 --> 02:10:43,753
I would expect the man who made it

1900
02:10:43,794 --> 02:10:48,591
to show the same care and devotion
in every aspect of his life.

1901
02:10:50,634 --> 02:10:52,386
Thank you.

1902
02:10:55,264 --> 02:10:56,307
Commodore!

1903
02:10:56,390 --> 02:10:58,100
What about Sparrow?

1904
02:11:00,019 --> 02:11:02,938
Oh, I think we can afford
to give him one day's head start.

1905
02:11:09,445 --> 02:11:11,113
So...

1906
02:11:12,198 --> 02:11:15,284
This is the path you've chosen, is it?

1907
02:11:16,660 --> 02:11:18,954
After all...

1908
02:11:18,996 --> 02:11:20,539
…he is a blacksmith.

1909
02:11:21,540 --> 02:11:22,792
No.

1910
02:11:27,505 --> 02:11:29,799
He's a pirate.

1911
02:11:54,824 --> 02:11:56,492
Heave!

1912
02:12:06,043 --> 02:12:08,629
Thought you were supposed
to keep to the code, eh?

1913
02:12:08,671 --> 02:12:11,340
We figured they were more actual...

1914
02:12:11,424 --> 02:12:13,384
...guidelines. [chuckles]

1915
02:12:17,513 --> 02:12:19,223
Thank you.

1916
02:12:20,349 --> 02:12:21,725
Captain Sparrow.

1917
02:12:26,021 --> 02:12:27,606
The <i>Black Pearl</i> is yours!

1918
02:12:43,414 --> 02:12:45,040
On deck, you scabrous dogs!

1919
02:12:45,124 --> 02:12:46,792
- Hands to braces!
- [squawks]

1920
02:12:46,876 --> 02:12:48,961
Let go and haul to run free.

1921
02:12:50,629 --> 02:12:52,423
Now...

1922
02:12:52,506 --> 02:12:54,341
Bring me that horizon.

1923
02:12:56,635 --> 02:12:59,430
[humming <i>A Pirate's Life for Me</i>]

1924
02:13:01,640 --> 02:13:03,726
<i>♪ …and really bad eggs</i>

1925
02:13:07,062 --> 02:13:09,565
<i>♪ Drink up, me hearties
Yo ho ♪</i>
